<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Bush vows to fight off Buchanan challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, MANCHESTER, NEW HAMPSHIRE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush took his re-election campaign to the south yesterday
in an attempt to restore his flagging electoral fortunes, and promised a
no-holds-barred battle against Mr Patrick Buchanan, his rightwing Republican
challenger.
Mr Buchanan's unexpectedly strong performance in Tuesday's New Hampshire
primary is a triumph for the television commentator whose campaign tapped
widespread discontent over Mr Bush's handling of the economy.
The size of the protest vote against the president embarrassed Mr Bush's
supporters and elated Democrats, who believe they have a strong chance of
defeating him in November's presidential election.
Mr Bush said he had still scored a 'good victory' with 58 per cent of the
Republican vote, against Mr Buchanan's 40 per cent. 'I'm not saying I
wouldn't have liked to do better, but I'm satisfied with the results, and
now we're down here and we're going to take this guy on in every state,' he
said on a campaign visit to Tennessee.
Although Mr Buchanan is not expected to endanger Mr Bush's chances of
winning his party's nomination - especially as several states have refused
to allow him on to the primary ballot - he came closer to the incumbent than
any challenger since Mr Ronald Reagan startled President Gerald Ford in
1976.
Republicans fear that Mr Buchanan could split the party, damaging its
chances in November's election.
Now that the conservative coalition, which has given the Republicans a near
stranglehold on the presidency since 1968, is showing signs of crumbling, Mr
Buchanan's long-term target appears to be the soul and perhaps even the body
of the Republican party in the years ahead.
Mr Bush campaigned for only four days in New Hampshire, but he will step up
the pace with several trips to southern states, which will see a series of
critical primaries over the next three weeks.
This culminates in the Super Tuesday contest on March 10, when 11 states
will cast their votes.
Mr Bush attempted to minimise the significance of Mr Buchanan's strong
showing in New Hampshire, calling it a protest vote from a state that has
been severely hurt by recession.
The president's advisers said New Hampshire would prove a high water mark
for the Buchanan campaign.
But Mr Buchanan said his relative success had given him the momentum to take
the Republican nomination from Mr Bush. 'If an incumbent president with his
resources and his machinery and the White House and the entire establishment
cannot do any better than that, I think they should really stand down,' he
said.
Mr Bush acknowledged the weakness of his performance and promised a tougher
campaign. 'All I did was lay back and get hammered by these Democrats and,
to some degree, by Pat,' he said. 'I've been in tough fights before and I'm
looking forward to this one.'
In New Hampshire, he avoided attacking Mr Buchanan or even mentioning his
name. Yesterday, he threatened some of the ferocious advertising that he
used to destroy Mr Michael Dukakis, his Democratic opponent in 1988. Mr Bush
warned: 'I've been very kind and gentle. I'll still be kind, and I'm now
debating how gentle to be.'
Mr Bush also took aim at his Democrat opponents, noting that Mr Paul
Tsongas, who won his party's primary in New Hampshire with 35 per cent,
disapproved of the economic programme put forward by Democrat leaders in
Congress.
Mr Tsongas and Governor Bill Clinton of Arkansas, who came a strong second
in New Hampshire with 26 per cent of the vote, have emerged as the
Democratic frontrunners.
Early recovery in the US economy and inflation at its lowest for a
generation was predicted yesterday by Mr Alan Greenspan, US Federal Reserve
chairman. Page 22
Democratic campaigners turn to a broader canvas Page 6
Editorial Comment
Battle for the soul Page 20
</TEXT>
