<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Heseltine spars with Labour over recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HIGHLY CHARGED fore-taste of the general election campaign set pulses
racing in the Commons last night as the two main parties clashed furiously
over the roots of the recession.
As Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, poured scorn on Tory claims that
the stalled recovery was a consequence of a worldwide downturn, Mr John
Major indicated in a newspaper interview that he was ready to authorise more
public spending in the Budget to kick start the economy.
Repeating his claim that the UK was now 'poised' for an upturn, the prime
minister said recovery had been delayed by a general lack of the 'confidence
factor'.
Mr Major's admission that he would raise the public sector borrowing
requirement came in an interview with The Daily Telegraph today ahead of a
cabinet meeting on Budget strategy.
Earlier Mr Smith had made clear he would unveil the details of Labour's tax
and spending plans after the March 10 Budget was announced and before an
election.
The economy dominated the day at Westminster as Labour's ferocious assault
on the government's record met an equally spirited counter-attack from Mr
Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary.
Amid fierce barracking from the government benches, Mr Smith charged the
Tories with blaming foreigners for their failures and being 'unwilling and
incapable of moving the country out of recession'.
But his attack was brushed aside by Mr Heseltine who counter-claimed that
the Labour leadership was riven with divisions about how to respond to the
downturn.
Against the mounting election fever at Westminster, the recession debate had
been widely - and rightly - anticipated as a 'clash of giants'. Mr Heseltine
had been drafted in to answer Mr Smith because Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, was giving evidence to the Treasury committee.
Mr Smith used his opening speech to review the government's pledges of an
early economic upturn. He went on to pour scorn on claims that recovery had
been halted by an international recession.
Earlier explanations from ministers that the causes of the recession were
rooted in such factors as deregulation of the financial sector were proof it
was 'home-grown, domestically caused and without a hint of a foreign
bacillus', he said.
Ignoring the charges, a clearly relaxed Mr Heseltine countered that the key
issue was not the cause of the downturn, but how to respond to it. To the
delight of his backbenches, he went on to cite newspaper reports of
divisions within the Labour leadership.
'This debate started off as a vote of confidence in the government's
economic policies,' Mr Heseltine said. 'It has rapidly become a vote of
confidence in the shadow cabinet.'
His light-hearted teasing of the Labour frontbench provoked outrage from the
opposition, but clearly raised morale among Tory MPs who described his
speech as a 'vintage performance'.
The government had a majority of 100 when it came to the vote, with the
Labour attack defeated by 311 to 211.
Earlier, Labour had stepped up its assault on the Tories' economic record
when Mr Smith, claimed the government had cost every household Pounds 2,200
last year alone.
The figure - centrepiece of a new document entitled The Cost of the
Conservatives - came as a clear response to the Tories' recent poster
campaign alleging Labour would raise taxes by an average of Pounds 1,000 per
taxpayer.
It is based on a calculation that the government's 'economic incompetence'
had delivered the worst growth record since the second world war, resulting
in the UK economy foregoing some Pounds 50bn in gross domestic product last
year.
Sitting beneath a poster of Mr Lamont in a stocking mask alongside the
slogan 'You've Been Robbed', Mr Smith told a Westminster news conference
that 'everyone now knows' Britain was suffering the deepest recession since
the 1930s.
He said the Pounds 50bn GDP shortfall represented the gap between a 2.5 per
cent average growth trend, established from 1955 until 1979, and the
'miserable' 1.7 per cent annual growth actually achieved.
Retail sales up 0.4% in month, Page 8
Labour's tax and spending plans, Page 10
Observer, Page 20
Samuel Brittan: 2 3/4 cheers for a hung parliament, Page 21
</TEXT>
