<PROFILE>_AN-CBTB0ADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920220
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Survey of Vehicle Fleet Management (8): Cashing in on a
greener image - Profile of Gateway Foodstores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACK SEMPLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GATEWAY Foodstores, with 1,100 cars in the fleet, is contributing to a
steady rise in the popularity of diesels. It started buying diesels in
earnest in August last year, and now has 200.
The retailer was already considering a move to diesels, especially in the
mid-range of its fleet, to reduce costs and improve reliability, when a
corporate commitment to environmental improvement swung the balance in
favour of switching to an all-diesel policy, across the fleet. The 'green'
benefit will come from reduced carbon dioxide emissions.
Brian Tomlin, commercial manager, sees diesels giving clear advantages over
petrol in other areas. Reliability emerged as a key issue. Niggling faults,
especially on electricals, start to creep in on petrol cars after about
60,000 miles, and garages do not seem to know enough about the vehicles to
cope with them efficiently and the risk of unit failure increases
significantly after 80,000 miles, he says. The company had extended petrol
car mileages from a maximum of 75,000 to 85,000.
Mr Tomlin says that while that is uncomfortably high for petrol cars, 'we
don't feel at all at risk, operationally, taking diesels up to 3.5 years or
85,000 miles'. Once the firm has more experience of the cars, these limits
could be extended to 100,000 or more.
Mr Tomlin feels much safer on residual values with diesels: 'You can get the
fright of your life from Glass's Guide, looking at what happens to trade
prices for petrol cars between 50,000 and 100,000 miles.' Diesels, on the
other hand, remain popular and retain strong residuals, right up to 100,000
miles.
The classic means of retaining high residuals is to replace cars at least as
frequently as every 40,000 miles. 'However, this leaves you exposed to heavy
capital demands, if you want to extend vehicle life temporarily, then go
back to frequent changes,' Mr Tomlin says.
Overall, he expects maintenance costs to be around 5 per cent lower using
diesels, in spite of slightly more frequent oil and filter changes. Costs
are about the same up to 40,000 miles, but start to creep up on petrol cars
after that.
The biggest cost savings are on fuel, and come at the heart of the fleet
market, the medium-sized saloons. Gateway was running 400 Sierra 1.6
petrol-engined cars - admittedly not the most frugal in its class -
returning an average fuel consumption of 30 miles per gallon (mpg). The
Sierra replacements, the Peugeot 405 and BX 19 diesels, both with the
increasingly popular PSA XUD turbo and naturally aspirated engines, are
giving around 45 mpg.
Not only are these cars using less fuel, but diesel can be substantially
cheaper than petrol - typically three pence a gallon in winter, and up to 16
pence a gallon the rest of the year. (Diesel prices are more subject to
seasonal fluctuations because of strong demand for fuel oil in winter.)
Overall, Mr Tomlin believes that company car fuel bills would fall by 40 per
cent across the fleet, given an instant change from all-petrol to
all-diesel.
This substantial saving derives partly from the concentration of
middle-sized cars. At the top and bottom end, percentage fuel savings are
more marginal.
Many diesel models continue to be priced higher than petrol equivalents, and
it can take 25-30,000 miles to recoup the extra with savings on fuel. The
differences in price exist for marketing, rather than engineering reasons,
and the gaps will close, Mr Tomlin predicts.
He sees other drawbacks with diesels. They are noisier, especially when cold
and at low revs, and this irritates some drivers. 'The gap between diesel
and petrol has narrowed, but I don't see that anyone will ever mistake the
two types of engine.'
In making the switch, Gateway has sweetened the pill by widening the choice
of marques available to its drivers. As the company gains experience of
diesels, the range will probably be narrowed to three or four makes for most
employees, to concentrate purchasing power.
There is still not nearly enough choice at the top end of the market, Mr
Tomlin says. The Mercedes-Benz 300D is offered to executives who previously
had larger Mercs, Jaguars and the BMW 7-series, but it is considered by some
to have too small a cabin. The BMW 525 diesel turbo, due by September, will
make a welcome addition to the available options.
Diesel poses problems, at present, to employees at the lowest tax bracket.
The Citroen AX with the 1360 engine is offered to drivers who previously had
Escort 1300s.
Mr Tomlin is concerned, too, at the lack of automatic options. for the time
being, the only option for many drivers is the Citroen BX.
Gateway buys its cars and services a third of them at its own workshop in
Bristol, which trades as Hartcliffe Motors. Already, the diesels are proving
simpler and cheaper to service, Mr Tomlin enthuses. Elsewhere, and
especially in London, the company is having a proportion of servicing done
by independent, rather than franchised, workshops.
Diesels have, until now, been sold short in Britain by market leaders Ford
and Vauxhall, which have treated them as second-division products, Mr Tomlin
believes. Peugeot and Citroen, with their XUD engines, found themselves
holding the key to a niche market, and the rest of the market is only now
responding. 'The diesel market is set to take off, for sound engineering,
cost and environmental reasons,' he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Photograph Brian Tomlin, sweetened the pill by widening the
choice (Omitted).
</PAGE>
