<PROFILE>_AN-CBTB0ADRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920220
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Survey of Vehicle Fleet Management (7): New look to the car
park - Profile of National &amp; Provincial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACK SEMPLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'busy bee' building society, National &amp; Provincial, has scrapped its
conventional company car system, under which it owned 400 cars. Instead, it
has introduced a radical programme of cash allowances, and loans to every
'company car' driver to buy whatever he or she wishes.
The new scheme was launched last October and already the car park at the
headquarters in Bradford looks radically different. Gone is the
concentration of recently-registered stalwarts from the fleet market, in
N&amp;P's case Jaguar for senior executives, then Rover 800, Vauxhall, and, at
the bottom end, Ford.
There is now a liberal mix of vehicles: more drivers, free from punitive tax
bands, have gone for cars with engines of more than 2 litres; there is an
unusually high proportion of estates, for the family; and you can see a few
Land Rover Discoverys, a popular all-rounder in rural Yorkshire. 'Cars have
become a matter for individual choice - as they should be,' Paul Chapman,
director of business and organisation development, explains.
The switch to the new system has several main objectives, but cost reduction
is not one, Mr Chapman says. Most importantly, the company wanted 'to get
rid of the status thing which surrounds company cars'.
They have long been an unnecessary source of conflict between 'haves' and
'have-nots'. Also, even among those who have company cars, the perceived
benefit varies from one employee to another, especially as the workforce
becomes more mixed, and is no longer dominated by prototype male
breadwinners.
Basic administration was a burden on the company - not a great one, but the
buying, selling, insurance, processing of claims and so on distracts from
the main business.
The new system of cash allowances will allow N&amp;P to respond more effectively
to further changes in the tax structure of company cars.
N&amp;P's 400-strong fleet was split evenly between those which were primarily
perks, or 'benefit cars', and 'need' cars, supplied to staff such as
salesmen and valuers for whom a car is essential.
The benefit cars were on a three-year, 60,000 miles replacement cycle, while
the need cars were renewed after two years or 40,000 miles. These are now
the starting points for working out individual cash allowances. They are
calculated by taking the retail price of the car allocated to the employee's
grade within the company, the 'benchmark value', adding the estimated
straight line depreciation, maintenance and other costs, then deducting the
net tax saving for the individual.
The allowance is paid monthly, grossed up for tax. It is shown as a separate
item, although it could, logically, be consolidated with the salary. That
might be moving too far ahead of the market, however. 'We would want to see
what our competitors are offering, before we made that decision,' says Mr
Chapman.
The company offers employees four-year loans towards the cost of the car,
again related to the benchmark value, and tax-free up to the first Pounds
10,000 - the limit for tax-free loans under the society's rules.
Employees can benefit by buying second-hand and saving on depreciation,
something which would be much less acceptable as a company fleet policy.
Chapman's own car is a good example. Under the old scheme, he would have
been due a new Jaguar, reflecting his senior status in the company. In fact,
he has bought a sporty two-year-old Toyota Supra. List price, new, is Pounds
26,000 but he bought his from a local dealer for Pounds 13,000, with the
warranty extended for a further four years.
Not only does he have a car he prefers, he will gain financially. The car
had already suffered its heavy depreciation when he bought it, and by the
end of the third year, say, the car will be worth substantially more than
the value of the outstanding loan.
The cash allowance scheme is being closely monitored, Mr Chapman says, and
each driver's circumstances are reviewed every six months. Adjustments may
be made to the scheme, for example, to give employees a degree of protection
against the sharp depreciation in the first two years of a new car.
Any direct financial benefit to the society is marginal, and cost savings
were not the object of the change, Mr Chapman said. There should be cost
savings to the 'company car' economy as a whole, as employees are likely to
look after their vehicles more carefully. Many are expected to be passed on
to spouses, or other relatives.
Surprisingly, perhaps, employees are paying little more, in the present
economic climate, than N&amp;P was, either for new cars or for servicing. N&amp;P
has left its fuel payment system unchanged, to avoid making an already
complicated change more difficult. Those with cars on a 'need' basis claim
back fuel expenses, while those using cars as benefits use Dial fuel cards.
The principles behind the cash allowances scheme can be applied for a wider
range of company perks - car parking, low-cost mortgages and pension fund
contributions could eventually come up for review, for much the same reasons
as the car fleet system has been overhauled.
Mr Chapman believes the new scheme gives N&amp;P a slight edge in recruiting
good new staff. In spite of some initial misgivings, 'it has gone down quite
well, especially as people have come to recognise the individual
responsibility and choice involved', he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-7864</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBTB0ADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920220
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Survey of Vehicle Fleet Management (5): Wide choice of cars
for employees - Profile of Johnson Matthey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHNSON MATTHEY offers its employees a very wide range of company cars from
which to choose. Even the most junior employee entitled to a company car has
a choice from about 75 models from nine manufacturers. But, as might be
expected from the world's largest platinum group metals marketing
organisation, the company stipulates that every car must be fitted with an
anti-pollution catalyst.
Automotive catalysts are now the biggest consumers of platinum metals and
JM, which is one of the largest catalyst producers, has many of the world's
motor companies among its customers.
So virtually every car manufacturer offering cars with catalysts in the UK
is on JM's list of approved vehicles.
This list was extended two years ago and other changes made to ensure more
employees received cars of their choice. JM allocates cars on an
hierarchical basis but has blurred the lines between categories by
permitting employees to contribute some of their own cash towards company
cars. An employee can add up to an extra 10 per cent to the monthly cost to
get a better car. Employees pay the extra by way of a 'private use' charge.
Mr Terry Stock, JM's group personnel controller, says: 'Providing cars is an
expensive benefit - we spend about Pounds 2m a year - yet two years ago
people were complaining because they could not have the cars they wanted. It
made sense to change the system slightly so that, at no extra cost, they
could have the cars they wanted.' However, like many other companies, JM
frequently reviews its company car operations and Mr Stock says there is no
guarantee the system would not be changed if there were substantial savings
from having a less-flexible approach.
Already the impact of the recession has forced a change of policy and JM's
cars are now increasingly being retained for four years or 60,000 miles
instead of the three years or 60,000 which was the norm until recently.
'Modern cars can run for 80,000 miles with no trouble,' Mr Stock explains,
'but keeping a car for four years is stretching it a bit when it comes to
employee satisfaction.'
So, would JM switch back to a three-year policy when the economy picks up?
'I would not expect an immediate return,' he says. 'But the change will
probably be market-driven. When other companies move back to three years, we
may have to follow.' Mr Stock says the Chancellor's introduction of National
Insurance charges on the assumed financial benefit of company cars means JM
will hold as firmly as possible to the present 'benchmark' costs. So, when
car prices go up, employees might find the vehicle of their choice has moved
into a higher category.
The successively fierce increases in the personal tax charged on company car
benefits have caused some JM employees to ask for the benefit to be provided
by some other means. Typically these are employees whose spouses also have
company cars and who do not want to pay the tax on both. Mr Stock says that
requests for a change in the benefit are dealt with on an individual basis.
JM once bought all its company cars for cash. However, in 1984 it completed
a sale-and-leaseback arrangement with Avis and in August of that year signed
a contract hire deal with that company.
In the intervening years Avis has had several changes of management and even
an ownership change. There have also been times when its performance slipped
below what JM considered was the minimum level. So there have been occasions
when competing companies were asked to quote and individual operating units
within JM considered moving away from Avis.
But Avis Lease and Fleet Management still has the contract - a full-service
agreement covering all JM's 378 cars. Mr Stock says: 'I suppose it is a
question of 'better the devil you know'. But Avis understands us and has
worked with us and has responded well to criticism in the past.'
He says JM tries to have as little as possible internal involvement with
operating the car fleet. Nevertheless, he spends some of his time at group
headquarters setting policy - which must be agreed by JM's chief executive's
committee - while each operating unit has a fleet manager to provide liaison
between employees and Avis.
Employees are expected to look after their company cars and there have been
cases where people have been disciplined for failing to do so.
When employees have what Mr Stock calls 'driving problems', they are sent
for special driving tuition offered as part of the Avis package.
There is an unwritten rule at JM that employees cannot choose sports cars or
off-road vehicles unless they can make out a very good case for having them.
Mr Stock says nobody at JM has complete freedom of choice of car. The
remuneration committee of the board has to approve vehicles used by the
company's senior management. A few big executive cars are bought outright by
the company, 'although we're looking at leasing now'.
At the other end of the scale, the 'benchmark' car costs JM Pounds 327.66 a
month. It is a Vauxhall Cavalier, four-door 1.8 litre - with a catalyst, of
course.
</TEXT>
