<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / International Company News: Honeywell drops to Dollars
102.6m in last quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONEYWELL, the US controls group, reported fourth-quarter net income of
Dollars 102.6m, compared with Dollars 109.2m a year earlier, in spite of the
impact of the US and international economic recession.
The profits, which worked through at Dollars 1.46 a share, compared with
Dollars 1.49, were struck on sales which rose 2.3 per cent to Dollars
1.71bn, with each of the company's three main businesses showing revenue
gains.
The group's operating profit was Dollars 199.4m, down from Dollars 203.9m.
Honeywell said operating profits had improved in the home and building
control and industrial businesses, and remained steady in space and
aviation.
For the full year, the company reported net income of Dollars 331.1m, or
Dollars 4.70 a share, against Dollars 382m, or Dollars 5.03, in 1990.
However, the 1990 figures benefited from a lower tax rate - 28 per cent
against 35 per cent - as well as a gain of Dollars 14.3m from asset sales
and Dollars 10m of income from discontinued operations.
Mr James Renier, chairman, said the 'stable, solid results' were a dramatic
improvement over past recessions, and reflected the success of its strategy
in concentrating on the core control business.
The home control division earned fourth-quarter operating profits of Dollars
88.5m, up 3.5 per cent, while orders showed a double-digit increase. The
industrial business made Dollars 66.2m, up from Dollars 65.6m, with a modest
increase in orders.
</TEXT>
