<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / BAe maintains dividend despite Pounds 81m loss: Shares rise
11% as City welcomes strengthened cash flow Defence profits increase to
Pounds 500m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE reported yesterday a pre-tax loss of Pounds 81m last year
compared with a pre-tax profit of Pounds 376m in 1990.
The result was much in line with City expectations but better-than-expected
cash flow in the second half of last year, as a result of a reduction of
working capital, sent BAe shares 11 per cent higher. The shares closed
yesterday at 303p, up 30p in a day which saw the highest volume of trading
in the company's shares since July 1988.
The company maintained its final dividend at 16.1p bringing the total for
the year to 25p a share, the same as 1990.
Profits before tax and exceptional items amounted to Pounds 154m against
Pounds 400m. This was Pounds 4m higher than its autumn forecast.
Exceptional restructuring charges of Pounds 235m were taken to cover the
company's rationalisation programme.
However, after a substantial cash outflow in the first half of last year,
the company said it achieved an underlying cash inflow of Pounds 630m in the
second half mainly because of strength in its defence activities and a
reduction in working capital at its Rover car subsidiary.
With the benefit of its Pounds 432m rights issue, the company finished last
year with a net cash balance of Pounds 323m against Pounds 711m.
BAe's defence business accounted for the lion's share of the group's
earnings with trading profits before interest of Pounds 500m compared with
Pounds 486m. Commercial aircraft operations reported a trading loss of
Pounds 37m compared with a surplus of Pounds 14m. The regional aircraft
operations faced particularly difficult market conditions, said Sir Graham
Day, BAe's interim chairman.
The Rover car subsidiary faced tough market conditions but contained trading
losses before interest to Pounds 52m, compared with Pounds 65m the year
before.
The property development business saw its losses grow to Pounds 24m last
year from Pounds 8m, while construction activities increased profits to
Pounds 40m from Pounds 28m.
The group's total sales were virtually flat at Pounds 10.56bn last year
compared with Pounds 10.54bn in 1990.
Sir Graham said BAe expected to appoint a chairman and finance director at
its annual meeting in April or May.
Commercial aircraft side deeper in loss, Page 25; Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
