<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If British, European and world champion Wilf O'Reilly doesn't win the gold
medal in the 1000m short track speed skating final in the Winter Olympics
today it won't be for lack of interest among the broadcasters. The poor old
BBC have had so few British contestants to follow that they have gone wild
over Wilf. David Coleman will be describing his efforts in Olympics Today on
BBC2 (6.00) and again in Olympics 92 on BBC1 (11.25).
Happily Red Dwarf returns for a fifth series (9.00 BBC2). This is not
necessarily the most intellectually stimulating comedy ever written but it
does have several advantages: instead of being set in suburbia it is set in
a space ship, and instead of being middle-aged it is youthful. Having one
character who is a hologram and another who is a robot definitely extends
the comedy potential.
One of America's most popular middlebrow soaps also returns: LA Law
continues to mix the legal, social and sexual lives of its characters into a
steaming brew (9.00 ITV).
Channel 4 comes to the end of its series about The Germans (9.00) while BBC2
continues its series about the Spanish: Fire In The Blood (9.30).
</TEXT>
