FT  20 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Backbench attempt to break deadlock
 -Sunday Shopping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FRESH attempt to break the deadlock on reform of the Sunday trading laws
was made yesterday in a backbench bill which would allow limited types of
shop to open but sets stiffer penalties for those which break the law.
General stores, petrol-station shops, souvenir shops in zoos, museums or
parks, antique shops and shops at sportsgrounds would be allowed to open at
any time on a Sunday, as could petrol stations and airport shops.
Supermarkets would not be allowed to do so.
Other shops, such as garden centres and chemists would be able to open for
more limited periods. Stores trading illegally on a Sunday could face fines
of Pounds 50,000.
Although the new opening hours would apply only to England and Wales, the
bill would extend to Scotland in its protection of employees against
dismissal for refusing to work on a Sunday.
The bill, to be debated tomorrow, has some cross-party support, but .
