<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Israel launches new attacks in Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL launched renewed air and artillery attacks on targets in southern
Lebanon yesterday after an Israeli town was hit by rockets fired across the
border by Lebanese militiamen seeking revenge for the killing of Sheikh
Abbas Musawi, leader of the Shi'ite Moslem fundamentalist organisation
Hizbollah.
The fighting, the most intense in the area for years, went on unabated for
the third day running following the death of Mr Musawi in a rocket strike by
Israeli helicopters in south Lebanon on Sunday.
It prompted Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to warn that Israel was ready to
use 'all our might' to stop the rocket attacks on its territory, although he
denied suggestions that he was planning a large-scale action similar to the
1982 Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
He was speaking after visiting a bus station in an Israeli border town hit
by Katyusha rockets yesterday, the most dramatic Hizbollah strike to date.
No one was injured, but 13 people were treated for shock. Residents of
Kiryat Shemona and other border towns have spent much of the time since
Sunday in bomb shelters.
Later, Israel rocketed from the air - apparently using US-supplied Apache
assault helicopters - an alleged Hizbollah base in the village of Jibsheet.
No-one was reported hurt.
Iranian-backed Hizbollah, which normally confines its actions to attacks on
Israeli forces and their local allies occupying a strip of Lebanese
territory, has fired dozens of Katyushas across the Lebanese-Israeli border
since Mr Musawi was killed.
'They have a lot of Katyushas, but we will overcome them and disarm them,'
Mr Shamir said. 'There is no doubt the (army) and the whole state and all
our might are ready to give the answers which will grant the whole area
security."
Mr Ariel Sharon, the housing minister who as defence minister led the 1982
invasion, was reported by Israel Army radio as calling for a northward
extension of the 'security zone' controlled by Israeli forces to push the
Hizbollah rockets out of range of the border.
But Mr Shamir said: 'It will not be the same as it was in 1982. I think in a
few days we will have full security.'
Officials in the area said Israeli shelling of Hizbollah strongholds, which
has driven hundreds of local residents to flee their villages, intensified
sharply after the bus station attack.
Casualties have been surprisingly light in the fighting, which Israeli
authorities hope will gradually subside.
Fighting rages after Sheikh Abbas Musawi's murder
</TEXT>
