FT  20 FEB 92 / UN official to deliver warning to Saddam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE head of the UN commission overseeing the destruction of Iraq's most
dangerous weapons is going to Baghdad to warn of serious consequences if
President Saddam Hussein continues to defy Security Council resolutions,
writes Michael Littlejohns, UN correspondent in New York.
Mr Rolf Ekeus was directed last night to make the trip after he reported at
a closed-door council meeting that Iraq continued to display 'serious,
grave, even appalling disdain' for the world body and its decisions.
He will undertake the mission amid continuing speculation about possible US
measures to overthrow Mr Saddam.
Mr Ekeus has constantly complained of Iraqi duplicity in its attempts to
hide weapons of mass destruction and failure to meet even some of the most
elementary obligations in mandatory UN resolutions. Baghdad says the
requirements are excessively intrusive and violate its sovereignty.
Meanwhile Iraq has told the UN it plans to send a high-level delegation to
New York to plead in the Council for the lifting of sanctions.
The Iraqis seem certain to claim that sanctions are hurting old people,
women and children. However, Mr Saddam's refusal to accept UN terms set last
August for a limited lifting of the oil embargo to provide funds for
medicines and other humanitarian supplies will not help his case.
President George Bush and Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, both
emphasised during last month's Security Council summit session that
sanctions must continue. Mr Bush said they could not be removed while Mr
Saddam remained in power.
</TEXT>
