<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Ukrainian leaders see little future for CIS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Ukrainian leaders believe the Commonwealth of Independent States is
doomed as an effective long-term force and will have only a 'transitional'
function in enabling the states of the former Soviet Union to go their own
way.
Mr Ivan Pliushch, chairman of the Ukrainian parliament, said the CIS was a
'form which helps the states of the former Soviet Union go through a divorce
process'. The CIS, he said, was 'on the edge of a precipice' and he accused
Russia of seeking to re-establish union structure. 'Under the cover of
co-operation, they really wish to govern.'
Mr Mykola Mykhalchenko, chief political adviser to the Ukrainian president,
said the meeting of CIS heads of state in Minsk last Friday 'decided
nothing' and held out little hope that more definite decisions would be
taken at their next meeting in Kiev in March.
Prof Volodymyr Vasylenko, a senior adviser to the Ukrainian government, said
the Ukraine would seek to avoid an open rift before 1994, the deadline for
removing all nuclear weapons from the republic.
The Ukrainian view of the Commonwealth as an institution designed for
breaking apart rather than working together is at odds with that of other
member states and could influence western policy towards the former Soviet
Union.
Western anxieties have already been raised by the deterioration in relations
between Ukraine and Russia, the two largest CIS states. Military tension
between them has risen after six bombers were flown from a base in Ukraine
to Russia and Ukraine retaliated by taking over a strategic bomber base near
Kiev.
Mr Leonid Kravchuk, Ukrainian president, speaking in Kiev to foreign
journalists yesterday, again attacked his Russian counterpart, Mr Boris
Yeltsin, for announcing a reduction in nuclear weapons in Washington earlier
this month without reference to the presidents of other states of the CIS
and demanded consultation in the future.
'I am not against a reduction of nuclear arms but it must be founded on
reality. We must know how the reduction will be carried out, in what
stages,' he said.
Ukrainian officials assert their republic's intention to apply for
membership of the Council of Europe and ultimately the European Community as
an independent state. Mr Pliushch said that he 'resented' the fact that
Russia was seeking to negotiate with European institutions on behalf of
other CIS states.
Mr Mykhalchenko said of Mr Yeltsin: 'The leader of Russia says one thing at
breakfast, another at lunch and a third at supper. This is impossible.'
Mr Kravchuk said that while he would not describe Russia as imperialist
there were 'imperialist forces within its government.'
</TEXT>
