<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (9): Busy gateway to China
 -Hong Kong is the most developed gateway into China, with travel companies
and hotels in the colony offering a range of tours, tickets and services. It
is probably quicker to get a visa in Hong Kong rather than apply early in
one's home country, writes Angus Foster.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LO WU was once no more than a rickety bridge across the Shenzhen river,
where visitors  - lucky enough to have permission - left the comforts of
Hong Kong and came face to face with the suspicions and aggression of
Chinese communism.
Now, more than ten years after China opened to the world, a new
multi-storeyed Customs Hall greets foreigners flush with travellers cheques
and 'compatriots' from Hong Kong or Taiwan laden with presents for mainland
relatives.
Suspicions have been replaced by indifference. More than 30m people passed
through Lo Wu last year, some of them Hong Kong residents commuting daily to
factories in southern China. As the country continues to try to attract
foreign businessmen and tourists, travelling within China has never been
easier.
Hong Kong is the most developed gateway into China with travel companies and
hotels in the colony offering a range of tours, tickets and services.
Visitors can also deal direct with China Travel Service (HK), a Chinese
state-owned organisation which oversees visas, bookings and reservations.
Visas can be processed in less than a day and cost between HKDollars 150 and
Dollars 480, depending on processing speed and numbers of entries required.
It is quicker, and probably cheaper, to get a visa in Hong Kong rather than
apply early in one's home country.
Many businessmen enter China on tourist visas since they are quicker to
process. Business visas require a letter of introduction from a sponsoring
organisation in China.
As China has opened up, making travel arrangements has become easier and
easier. Scheduled flights are now available between Hong Kong and more than
ten Chinese cities and chartered flights are also popular. Even medium-sized
destinations have foreign joint venture hotels which can be booked from Hong
Kong. Travellers cheques and credit cards are increasingly accepted while
the Hong Kong dollar, rather than the Chinese renminbi, is sometimes the
only acceptable currency in the south.
Visitors to China usually head for one of three initial destinations;
Guangzhou, or Canton in the Pearl River Delta near Hong Kong; Shanghai,
China's largest city; and Beijing, the capital and home to all ministries
and political bodies. Generally, travel options decrease the further north
you go.
Links between Hong Kong and Guangzhou are very well developed. China
Southern Airlines, part of state airline CAAC, operates three flights a day
to the city which cost between HKDollars 400-Dollars 590 one-way and take 40
minutes. However, Chinese airlines are often frightening, despite recent
improvements. Taking into account travelling times to and from airports,
flying to Guangzhou is probably not much quicker than taking a train.
Direct trains to Guangzhou leave from Kowloon and take just under two and a
half hours. There are four each day and single tickets cost HKDollars 183.
Tickets should be booked in advance through CTS. If the trains are full,
travellers with time on their hands can take a Hong Kong train to Lo Wu,
cross the border by foot then catch a train to Guangzhou from the other
side. However, this can mean total travelling time of more than four hours
because connections are sometimes poor.
By far the most romantic route is by nightly ferry which arrives in
Guangzhou early the next morning. Services on board are limited and you may
find yourself sharing a compartment. Tickets cost HKDollars 150-Dollars 250,
again available from CTS.
Guangzhou is the natural launching pad for visits throughout Guangdong
province, the favourite destination for Hong Kong executives doing business
in China. It is also used by some business people as the place to plug into
China's domestic travel network, some of which cannot be booked from Hong
Kong.
For example, flights from Guangzhou to other Chinese cities are cheaper than
direct flights from Hong Kong. Sometimes, tickets are available on domestic
flights when international flights to the same destination are full.
However, the same safety questions apply and domestic services are rapidly
filling up as the country becomes richer. Finally, extra time should be
allowed in case your optimism about China's travel system proves unfounded.
Shenzhen, just across the border from Hong Kong, opened a new airport last
year and this provides another option for linking into the domestic network.
Citybus, a Hong Kong bus company, operates daily bus services to Shenzhen
airport which cost HKDollars 100 and take two and a half hours. From
Shenzhen there are flights to Beijing, Shanghai, Kunming and Chengdu,
although none are daily.
Travellers headed for Shanghai have three options. The easiest is a flight
on Dragonair, an airline specialising in China routes which is partly owned
by Cathay Pacific. Dragonair has five flights a week to Shanghai, costing
HKDollars 1,290 one way. If these flights are full, CAAC operates daily
services on the two hour route.
For less urgent engagements, a train from Guangzhou to Shanghai takes about
32 hours and leaves each morning. On overnight Chinese trains a sleeping
berth (either hard or soft sleeper) is strongly recommended. Alternatively,
ferries from Hong Kong to Shanghai depart roughly twice a week and take 60
hours. Enjoy the on-board swimming pool or, perhaps, the HKDollars 5,600
'presidential suite.'
For Beijing, Dragonair flies five times a week and a one way ticket costs
HKDollars 1,850. CAAC flies daily. Trains are not an option, unless you have
three clear days  - two for travelling and one to recover.
Businessmen needing interpreters are often better off making arrangements
after arriving in China through their hotels. CTS can arrange interpreters,
which cost around HKDollars 2,000-Dollars 4,000 a day plus expenses, but
they are unlikely to be able to cover technical topics.
CONTACTS:
China Travel Service (HK): Head Office, 4 Fl., CTS House, 78-83 Connaught
Road Central, Hong Kong. Tel 853 3533, Fax 541 9777.
Dragonair reservations: Tel 736 0202.
CAAC reservations: Tel 861 0322.
Trade enquiries - Hong Kong telephone numbers:
Hong Kong Trade Development Council, 833 4333; (The London telephone number
for the TDC is 071 828 1661).
China Resources Trade Consultancy Co., 827 5181,
Chinese General Chamber of Commerce, 525 6385
The Hong Kong Chinese Enterprise Association, 827 2831
China Merchants Holdings Co Ltd, 542 8288
Chinese Manufacturers Association of Hong Kong, 545 6116
Chinese General Chamber of Commerce, 525 6385
Guangdong Enterprises (Holdings), 815 0906
Fujian Enterprises (Holdings), 546 8968
China Everbright Holdings, 529 9350
China International Trust and Investment Corporation, 861 0838.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
