<PROFILE>_AN-CBTBGAAKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (11): Key facts for the
business visitor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN TANG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Visa requirements
British citizens or UK passport holders' do not require visas and will
normally be allowed to stay for 12 months, initially.
Visitors from communist countries, certain Middle East countries and some
East European countries, as well as Taiwan, always require visas.
British Dependant Territories' citizens, Commonwealth citizens and nationals
from most West European countries can stay in Hong Kong for up to three
months without a visa.
Americans as well as nationals from several central and South American
countries require visas for a visit exceeding one month. Visitors should
check at British consulates, high commissions or visa offices before
departure.
Currency
The unit of currency is the Hong Kong dollar (HKDollars ) which is pegged to
the USDollars at a rate of about HKDollars 7.8 to USDollars 1. Other sample
rates in January, 1992: Pounds 1=HKDollars 13.92; DM1=4.87.
Banking
There are 168 licensed banks in Hong Kong and 780 securities dealers. The
main banks include:
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation: 748 3322.
Standard Chartered Bank: 886 8888.
Citibank: 821 7311
The main banks can assist visitors who do not maintain bank accounts with
them to transfer funds in and out of Hong Kong. There are certain
restrictions. Visitors can only get their remittance from abroad out of
Hongkong Bank in Hong Kong dollars and Citibank in either Hong Kong dollars
or US dollars.
Business services
Nearly all major hotels offer business facilities with full secretarial
services. A number have business centres with fully-equipped private offices
and conference rooms for rent. There are also private agencies offering
serviced offices. Support staff can also be provided. (For telephone numbers
refer to Yellow Pages or newspaper classified pages).
Rents vary a great deal with different agencies. For example, the rental
cost for a 100 sq ft office in Central district, equipped with telephone
line, fax machine and word processing machine, can range from HKDollars
5,700 to HKDollars 12,000 per month.
The lease can be on monthly, daily or even hourly basis. An hourly rental
fee can be between HKDollars 50 and HKDollars 200.
The Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre (864 7827) is the main venue
for conferences and exhibitions in Hong Kong. Hong Kong Tourist
Association's Convention and Incentive Travel Bureau (801.7111) provides
information and assistance to conference organisers.
Courier services
Most hotels offer courier services for a fee. The Post Office also runs a
overseas speedpost service (for enquiries, call 523 1071).
Leading couriers operating in Hong Kong are: DHL (tel. 765 8111); Federal
Express (tel. 730 3333); TNT Skypak (tel. 389 5279); UPS (tel. 735 3535).
Both DHL and Federal Express have collection centres in business districts
while DHL also offers a 24-hour pick-up service.
Customs allowance
As a free trade centre, Hong Kong allows most items to be carried in duty
free. The only dutiable items are tobacco, alcohol, cosmetics and petroleum
products. Visitors are allowed to bring in the following items duty-free for
their own use: one litre of alcohol, 200 cigarettes or 50 cigars or 250
grams of tobacco, 60ml of perfume and 250 ml of toilet water.
Trade commissions and chambers of commerce
American Consulate General: 521 1467, (Foreign Commercial Service).
Australian Trade Commission: 585 4133.
British Trade Commission: 523 0176.
Canadian Trade Commission: 810 4321.
French Trade Commission: 529 4316.
German Business Associations: 526 5481.
Italian Trade Commission: 846 6500.
South Korea Trade Centre(KOTRA): 545 9500.
New Zealand Trade Development Board: 526 7898.
Singapore Trade Commission: 528 6185.
American Chamber of Commerce: 526 165.
Australian Chamber of Commerce: 522 5054.
British Chamber of Commerce: 824 2211.
Canadian Chamber of Commerce: 526 3207
Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce: 529 9229.
Hong Kong Japanese Chamber of Commerce and Industry: 577 6129
Hotels
The peak season for visitors is from March to May and from September to
November.
Hong Kong Hotel Association operates a hotel booking service for their
member hotels in the airport buffer hall where visitors can make bookings
upon arrival or in advance by telephone (383 8380).
Accommodation
For long-term visitors, serviced appartments are sometimes cheaper and more
pleasant. Some examples are:
ATRIUM (at Pacific Place):a 606 sq ft studio costs HKDollars 23,500 per
month, minimum two months. Contact: tel. 844 3864  - Swire Property Ltd.
PARKVIEW (at Tai Tam Reservoir Road): a 625 sq ft flat with one bedroom
costs HKDollars 32,500 per month, daily rate HKDollars 1,600 plus 10%
service charge. A 1,220 sq ft flat with two bedrooms costs HKDollars 54,000
per month: daily rate, HKDollars 2,750 plus 10% service charge. Contact tel
no: 844 3864.
CONVENTION PLAZA apartments (above Convention and Exhibition Centre): a
1,543 sq ft flat with two bedrooms costs HKDollars 47,000-60,000 per month,
minimum three months. Contact tel no: 824 2828.
VICTORIA APPARTMENTAS (at Victoria Hotel): a 1,025 sq ft flat with one
bedroom costs HKDollars 26,100 - 28,900 per month: minimum, one month.
Contact tel no: 540 7228.
Government and umbrella organisations
Government Information Services: 842 8747.
Royal Observatory: 732 9472.
Trade Department: 398 5333.
Industry Department: 737 2573.
HK Tourist Association: 801 7177.
Trade Development Council: 584 4333.
Companies Registry: 867 2600.
Customs &amp; Excise Department: 852 1411.
Federation of HK Industries: 723 0818.
Textile Council of Hong Kong: 305 2898.
HK Toys Council: 723 0818.
HK Electronics Association Ltd 866 2669.
Federation of Hong Kong Garment Manufacturers: 721 1383.
Federation of Hong Kong Watch Trades and Industries: 523 3232.
Telecommunications
Local phone calls are free although some hotels charge a handling fee. Local
calls made at public pay-phones cost HKDollars 1. Visitors can also make
long distance calls by using international calling cards (eg AT&amp;T, British
Telecom Charge Card, Hello Card) or credit cards (VISA, American Express,
Diners Club, JCB and Mastercard) at selected service centres or specially
marked phones.
It is sometimes cheaper dialling from rather than to Hong Kong. For details,
call International Customer Services on 013.
The Post Office's Postfax service allows visitors to send facsimiles from
Hong Kong. (Enquiries: 847 1148)
Visitors should note that British-style telephone jacks are used in Hong
Kong.
Transport
Taxis are cheap by international standards; the fare is HKDollars 9 on
flagfall plus HKDollars 90c for every 0.25 km after the first 2km. Radio
booking surcharge is HKDollars 2 and baggage surcharge is HKDollars 3 for
each piece of luggage. A HKDollars 20 surcharge applies to cross-harbour
tunnel trips, a HKDollars 3 surcharge for rides through the Lion Rock, Junk
Bay and Aberdeen Tunnels. A ride from airport to Central district normally
costs about HKDollars 60 (including Dollars 20 surcharge); and to Tsim Sha
Tsui about HKDollars 30. For telephone numbers of taxi companies, refer to
the Yellow Pages.
THE MASS TRANSIT RAILWAY (MTR): The MTR underground railway has three lines
which cover Kowloon, Hong Kong Island and the New Territories. The fares
range from HKDollars 3 to HKDollars 7.5. Stored-value tickets (HKDollars 50,
Dollars 100, Dollars 200) can be used within a period of six months at
reduced fares outside rush hours.
STAR FERRY: Fare for a trip between Central and Tsim Sha Tsui costs
HKDollars 1.20 for the upper deck or HKDollars 1 for the lower deck. The
service runs from 6:30am to 11:30pm.
FERRIES TO MACAU: Jetfoils (tel. 859 6596), High-speed Ferries (803 2255),
Hydrofoils and Jetcats (523 2136). Tickets can be purchased in advance from
HK/Macau Ferry Terminal at Shun Tak Centre, Hong Kong Ticketmate offices or
by telephone using credit cards. Passengers are advised to buy return
tickets before departure.
Clubs
Hong Kong Club: 525 8251*
HK Cricket Club: 574 6266*
HK Football Club: 576 2808
Ladies' Recreation Club: 522 0151*
HK Foreign Correspondents' Club: 521 1511*
HK Country Club: 552 4165
Royal HK Golf Club: 670 1211*
American Club: 813 1784*
HK Overseas Bankers Club 521 2365*
Royal HK Jockey Club: 837 8111
* These clubs offer reciprocity. Usually a letter of introduction from the
reciprocal club or recommendation from a club member is required for using
the facilities.
Time differences
This list shows the hours fas (+) or slow (-) on Hong Kong Standard Time:
 ------------------------------
Bankgkok .............- 1
Beijing ............... 0
Frankfurt  ...........- 7
Geneva  ..............- 7
London GMT  ..........- 8
Manila  ..............  0
New York  ...........- 13
Paris  ...............  7
Rome  ............... - 7
Seoul  ............... +1
Singapore  ............ 0
Sydney  .............. +2
Tokyo  ............... +1
Toronto  ..........  - 13
Taipei  ..............  0
 ------------------------------
The media
NEWSPAPERS: Four English newspapers are printed in Hong Kong: South China
Morning Post, The Standard, Asian Wall Street Journal and International
Herald Tribune. The Financial Times and a wide selection of overseas papers
are also available.
TELEVISION: Two English channels broadcast by local stations; four English
satellite TV channels.
RADIO: RTHK Radio 3 (567 kHz), RTHK Radio 4 (97.6 to 98.9 mHz)  - classical
music, Commercial Radio (864kHz), British Forces Broadcasting Service (93.1
mHz), Metro News (1044 kHz), FM Select (104mHz). BBC World Service Relay
(675 kHz).
Useful publications
Hong Kong Tourist Association produces:
The Official Hong Kong Guide.
Associations and Societies in Hong Kong.
Directory of HK factory outlets and locally-made fashionware outlets.
The association's address is: Star Ferry Concourse, Kowloon. Basement,
Jardine House, Central.
The Government Publications Centre produces: Hong Kong Year Book; Hong Kong
Trade and Industrial Organisations; Hong Kong's Trade Outlook; annual
economic reports. The GPC address is: G/F, General Post Office Building,
Central.
A useful booklet, Hong Kong For The Business Visitor, is also available from
the Hong Kong Trade Development Council; tel.(5) 833 4333.
Further reading
Other useful material is available from book stores, with guides such as:
'Introduction to Hong Kong'; 'Hong Kong's Best Restaurants 92'; and 'The
Complete Guide To Hong Kong Factory Bargains.' MAIN BOOK STORES: South China
Morning Post Family Book Shop (Star Ferry Concourse, Ocean Centre);
Bookazine (Alexandra House, Central); Swindon Book Co Ltd (Ocean Terminal,
Tsim Sha Tsui); Hong Kong Book Centre (Landmark basement, Central).
See also panel in this guide on books for business and leisure.
Electricity
The supply is 200 volts.
