</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (5): It's all a gamble in
Macao - Bets of all kinds: whether at the crowded races in Hong Kong or in
the round-the-clock casinos of the neighbouring colony of Macao, the
Cantonese show their love for money and taking risks. But few get rich, says
Angus Foster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THEY stop talking. There is time for one last drag on a cigarette which is
then tossed below into the melee of shuffling feet, fast-food cartons and
crumpled newspapers listing triangles of numbers.
The crowd pours down another step, urged forward by latecomers who have
sweated anxiously in front of betting booths, wishing the queue would hurry,
watching the clock count down towards the off.
'Race Number 6 in 2 minutes' flashes across the giant electronic scoreboard
listing its own triangle of numbers, the odds for the next race. Blinking at
the bottom are totals betted on the race, win, place, tierce and quinella.
The figure passes HKDollars 100m and the crowd cheers.
This is Hong Kong racing: 50,000 people jammed into high rise stands in
Happy Valley, the tight bends of the track illuminated by floodlights and
the stadium, this amphitheatre of Mammon, dwarfed by surrounding tower
blocks.
The whole operation mixes avarice and enlightened despotism. Last year Hong
Kong people gambled more than HKDollars 47bn on horses, equal to the GDP of
Sri Lanka. Most of it is paid back as dividends. But few get rich. The Royal
Hong Kong Jockey Club, purveyor of the colonial monopoly for supplying this
gambling opiate, donates the surplus to charity and makes it all seem
respectable.
The slick sophistication of the game, and the exceptional facilities, should
make the Jockey Club in the 'home country' blush and provide strong
arguments in favour of doing away with bookies.
It is all slightly seedy, too. Leading trainers and jockeys, eulogised in
the press, are regular visitors to the colony's courts, some playing lead
roles and bit parts in sex scandals and race fixing jaunts. But all is
forgotten come the next meeting when attention turns to the racing pages and
jockey, horse, raceform and trainer are rolled into one, a blinking number,
calling like Sirens from the giant scoreboard.
Hong Kong's preoccupation with gambling is often sneered at: 'expats' feign
contempt for a Cantonese love of money, forgetting they themselves are
usually in Hong Kong for little else. But the contempt also masks envy. At
the races or in the casinos of the nearby Portuguese enclave of Macao, it is
the ability to go to the edge, to stare ruin in the face, to experience that
level of risk, which is most admired.
This is a human condition, not unique to Hong Kong or the southern Chinese.
The difference is that in Hong Kong, an immigrant society facing the fears
of 1997  - when all bets could be off  - life itself contains risks with
which most would be uncomfortable.
While this man gambles with his savings on the tables, that man is gambling
with his marriage by emigrating to Canada for a foreign passport, leaving
behind his wife and family. Or take that one, the young guy in a suit beside
you in the street: maybe he is gambling with his career, chucking it in for
a fast-buck job to try and get ahead in case, or before, things go wrong.
And the rest? There is the hope. Like the mainland Chinese tourist who last
year won close to Pounds 1m on a one-armed-bandit in Macao. Or the Hong Kong
man who backed a triple for HKDollars 4m. There is always the hope.
Macao also has a race track, gleaming new on Taipa island, the brain child
of Taiwanese businessmen. They had the vision of beaming racing from Macao
'live' to Taiwan, another immigrant Chinese community, once its ban on
gambling was lifted.
But the project failed to attract enough punters from Hong Kong, so it was
rescued by Mr Stanley Ho, Macao's gambling king, and his friends. Mr Ho
could well afford it: he is reckoned to own about one quarter of STDM, the
jealous guardian of Macau's gambling monopoly which pays more than HKDollars
2bn in taxes each year.
The casinos stay open around the clock. At each table the faces are
familiar, mainly working class Hong Kong people of varying ages. Families,
here for an hour on a day out, mix with veteran gamblers who will be here
tomorrow morning. Faces are lit by the hope, all eyes fixed on the card,
ball or button. When a game is over, the eyes look up and meet, sharing in
each other's communion.
Macao was overtaken by history when its harbour silted up and the British
moved 50 miles east across the Pearl River Delta to Hong Kong in 1841. The
Portuguese stayed behind and Macao has kept a Mediterranean tempo. Amidst
its walled villas and scented gardens, or standing among the crumbling
Catholic cathedral, there are few echoes of Hong Kong's intensity and drive.
Hong Kong views Macao rather like a relative who has fallen on hard times.
Macao's plans for a new airport, port and industrial zones are seen as
quaint but inconsequential, being dwarfed by Hong Kong's own projects.
But both colonies face the same future. Macau is to be handed back to
Chinese sovereignty in 1999, two years after Hong Kong. To them both, Peking
has given the same specious of promises of 'a high degree of autonomy' in
internal affairs.
While the red Chinese flag flutters discreetly in Hong Kong, it drapes a
casual arrogance in Macao. Except for a period of ugly tension during
China's Cultural Revolution, relations with the Portuguese have been better
than with Britain. China's wishes are rarely questioned in Macao.
Every evening, the coterie of gamblers and tourists heads for home
strapped-in aboard jetfoils, also courtesy of Mr Ho and his friends, which
ply the 45-minute route to Hong Kong. The craft buzz across the South China
Sea like sea planes unable to quite lift above the water.
On board there is time for one more gamble. A salesgirl walks the lines of
passengers and sells 'scratch and see' lottery tickets. She seems bored. Few
people risk their cash on the way home. She is peddling the hope, offering
one last fix before return to Hong Kong. There, life is less immediate than
gambling, and it will take several years to know if the bets have paid off.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII Photograph High-tec sports news at Happy Valley (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-8010</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBTBGAAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (2): Fresh signs of
confidence - The Economy: prospects are promising, but a threatened trade
war between the US and China could injure Hong Kong's manufacturing
industry.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG has the sort of economic problems that many a recession-obsessed
finance minister would sell a grandmother for: it saw real growth below five
per cent last year; there are acute labour shortages, with unemployment
below two per cent; it is struggling to take the steam out of a residential
property boom that lifted prices by 50 per cent last year; domestic exports
stagnated as manufacturers shifted operations over the border into China  -
moves that lifted re-exports by 28 per cent. It seems that every blessing is
mixed.
More genuine headaches hover, nevertheless. Inflation sticks doggedly over
10 per cent, driven by the labour shortages. Most unnervingly, a threatened
trade war between the United States and China could injure many of the
territory's toy, electronics and garment manufacturers. It is also unnerving
for an economy dominated by exports to see main export markets like the US
and the UK still deep in recession, with Japan and Germany slowing down.
A year ago, there was much greater cause for gloom. The Gulf War cast a
shadow over the world's economies, and brought Hong Kong's
critically-important tourist industry to a juddering halt. The war came as
the second body-blow to tourism in the territory: the Tienanmen massacre in
Beijing in June 1989 brought tourism in China to a grinding halt, and with
it the number of visitors transiting Hong Kong.
The ostracism of China that followed Tienanmen hurt exports from the
mainland, denting the volume of re-exports through Hong Kong. The result was
that in 1990, growth in the economy slowed to 2.8 per cent, while Hong
Kong's container port lost its place as world leader to Singapore.
The rebound since then has been strong. Tourist arrivals recovered to pass
6m in 1991 as Taiwanese visitors have poured into mainland China. This has
lifted hotel occupancy rates back above 75 per cent, even though eight new
hotels opened during the course of the year. Tourism earnings reached about
HKDollars 40bn for the year.
While exports to the US fell by 8 per cent on the year, and sales to Japan
stagnated, exports to Germany in particular, and Europe in general, more
than compensated, lifting total exports by almost 20 per cent for the year.
Hong Kong stands as the world's 11th largest trader, with exports of
HKDollars 89bn in 1991, and imports of HKDollars 90bn making a visible trade
total of HKDollars 179bn.
The Kwai Chung terminal handled 6.2m units over the year  - a record, and 20
per cent better than 1990. The terminal has recovered its leading world
position, once again leading Singapore and Rotterdam.
Consumer spending rose by almost 20 per cent, while residential property
prices leapt by 50 per cent in a six-month period, and are expected to surge
further ahead this year. This has provided a strong underpinning to the
local stock market, which rose by more than 40 per cent on the year,
bettered only by Mexico.
Stock market confidence has also been bolstered by the successful settlement
in January of a long-simmering dispute between the US and China on the
protection of patents and copyright.
Whether this confidence can be sustained will depend critically on a much
more serious and wide-ranging trade conflict between China and the US that
could jeopardise China's most favoured nation (MFN) status, due for renewal
in June.
It has become clear that loss of MFN status, which would lead to duties on
many Chinese exports of 100 per cent and more, would have a catastrophic
effect on the fast-growing export economy of southern China. Hong Kong's
manufacturers in China could not expect to be unscathed: they account for
about 25,000 factories, employing almost 3m people. As re-exports through
Hong Kong would be decimated, the territory would suffer indirectly as as
the volume of freight passing through the container port slumped.
It is estimated that port throughput would fall by 25 per cent, with more
than 40,000 jobs being lost in Hong Kong, and GDP growth cut by about 1.5
per cent.
Needless to say, the Hong Kong government, and manufacturing interests, are
lobbying Washington hard to prevent a trade war with China. But in an
election year, they are nervous that both Congress and the Bush
administration could act unpredictably.
With the exception of the MFN cloud, economic prospects otherwise appear
more promising. The government is forecasting economic growth to reach 5 per
cent this year  - below the 1980s average of 7.8 per cent, but respectable
by world standards.
Agreement with China to build a new airport in Hong Kong, which will involve
projects worth more than HKDollars 100bn over the coming six years, means
there will be strong domestic impetus behind economic growth, with labour in
very short supply for several years to come. The US market may take some
time to provide a fillip to exports, but growing demand throughout Asia
(including China) is likely to provide important compensation.
Most significant of all, the 1990s are likely to see the progressive decline
of Hong Kong as a manufacturer, with most production already shifting over
the border into China. Instead, the territory is emerging as a major
entrepot for China, and the effective capital of a south China region
encompassing 120m people in Guangdong, Fujian and Taiwan. It will also be
critical as a services hub for an increasingly prosperous east Asia region,
providing financial and business services, telecommunications links, and a
pivotal port and airport.
All in all, Britain's recession feels light years away.
