<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (4): The Chinese way of
working - Business and Social Etiquette: few people are as cosmopolitan and
tolerant as the Hong Kong Chinese, yet beneath the western veneer you have a
Chinese city that has very Chinese ways of working and playing, explains
David Dodwell.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS the taxi turned away from Kaitak airport and into the tightly packed
night-time streets of Kowloon  - an orgy of dubious tenement blocks and
garish neon  - it was impossible to ignore the tin containers scattered
along the pavements and on the street corners with flames leaping out of
them. Families were feeding paper money to the hungry ghosts.
Scratch Hong Kong's colonial and expatriate veneer and you have a Chinese
city that has very Chinese ways of working and playing. Its taipans may be
cosmopolitan enough to forgive a visiting barbarian his ignorance of these
ways, but without some knowledge, it will prove hard to share the moral high
ground.
A visiting business-person can get a long way with scant knowledge of hungry
ghosts. At the most fundamental level, most Chinese business people are
highly conservative. This means they dress conservatively, are uncomfortable
with body contact, and prefer a polite distance. They can be appalled by the
robust bonhomie typical of some American businessmen  - all shoulder hugs
and first name terms. Dressing conservatively means suit and tie for a man,
even in the soporific humidity of Hong Kong's summer months.
It is not only for reasons of etiquette that Chinese prefer to keep their
distance. Put bluntly, they find that many westerners smell. It's all to do
with being hairy, and open-pored. Lots of showers and deodorants will be
more than usually important  - and not only in torrid summer.
For a woman, crisp neutral elegance is safer than anything flamboyant. Both
white and royal blue are funeral colours among Chinese, so are best avoided.
There is a strong undercurrent of chauvinism among Chinese men which is
disguised by taboos on body contact, discrete body language, and the
presence of many Chinese women at the very highest levels of business,
government and industry. Behind a tendency to be dismissive of women is a
respect for those who apply a sharp, no-nonsense intelligence in their work.
So a visiting woman executive can earn respect, but should be under no
illusions that she will have more to prove than a male to win the confidence
of a Hong Kong client.
A lack of promptness will go down badly. Hong Kong works as a highly
efficient place, where the value of time is calculated carefully. The
physical compactness of the city means that many meetings can be crowded
into a day, from power breakfasts to after-dinner discussions. Just because
a meeting is over lunch, or dinner, or in a nightclub should not blind a
visitor to the fact the agenda is strictly business.
One US-educated Chinese businessman confided: 'I find it excruciating to
have a client chatting to me about his wife, her breast cancer, his
daughter's divorce, and other very personal details. It's so embarrassing. A
Chinese would never bring his personal life into a business meeting."
The result of this is that Chinese appear to many westerners to lack
polished edges. They tend to 'get straight down to business,' rather than
banter at the beginning of a meeting, and shuffle rather stiffly through the
pleasantries.
'If you think a Chinese businessman is unpolished, you may not be wrong,'
one Chinese executive notes: 'Some have little in the way of formal
education, and have got to where they have got by hard work and two bare
hands.'
This is less likely to be the case among younger Chinese. Those who arrived
in Hong Kong as refugees from China during the 1940s, 1950s and 1960s have,
where possible, made sure their children have had the educations they never
had chance to obtain.
As a result, the universities of Vancouver, San Francisco and London are
awash with diligent and successful Chinese students. Many have returned to
run their own, or family companies, or to swell the ranks of Hong Kong's
professional classes. The point to remember is that money, and business
acumen counts for more than a PhD. The result is a surprisingly meritocratic
respect for anyone who has acquired wealth, whether or not it is underpinned
by impressive academic success. At the same time, it is often sensible to
draw a discrete veil around the question of someone's origins, or how his
wealth was first amassed.
Linked with a powerful sense of personal dignity is the Chinese concept of
'face'. In fact, much more is made of face than is necessary, since
westerners have their own very similar concepts of giving or losing face. At
a practical level, it usually means more than treating people with respect
and politeness. In Hong Kong it may mean that difficult or confrontational
issues would if possible be dealt with by junior staff: it is thought
unseemly for taipans to exchange harsh words unless it is absolutely
necessary.
'Face' might also mean that someone whose grasp of English is uncertain will
pretend to understand even if he does not. It is important to remember that
one's counterpart is doing business in his or her second language. By
talking simply, avoiding idiomatic English, and encouraging one's
counterpart to summarise as a way of confirming understanding, later
embarrassment can be avoided.
Even among sophisticated, cosmopolitan young business people in Hong Kong
(and it is worth noting that Hong Kong is an extremely young society, with
many large companies run by people in their twenties and thirties),
'Chineseness' shows through in an all-pervasive regard for superstition.
Even those converted to Christianity show a healthy respect for the pantheon
of Taoist deities that populate the lives of the majority. Belief in natural
harmony  - the balance of the polar forces of yin and yang  - and of energy
forces flowing through the environment  - understood as the forces of
fengshui, or wind and water - reside deep in Chinese minds. So does ancestor
worship, belief in auspicious and inauspicious dates, and superstition
linked through word play and puns with lucky and unlucky numbers, colours
and words.
For a westerner, it is often enough to be a knowing observer on these
subconscious forces in every Chinese life. Sometimes, however, a more active
awareness may be called for. A telephone number with lots of '4s' in it, or
a hotel room on the 44th floor, would be seen as singularly inauspicious.
The number four in Chinese sounds much the same as the word for death. By
contrast, the numbers 3, 8 and 9 are full of good luck: the first sounds
like the word for life, the second for wealth, and the third for long life.
This may sound far-fetched, but it is bemusing to stand in the Central mass
transit railway station at rush hour and watch how reluctant passengers are
to exit through turnstile number 44.
Gifts for a client also need to be carefully chosen. A bell or a watch or
clock are unlikely to be welcome, since they suggest death is not far away.
In the unlikely event that shoes are being considered for a gift, forget it:
they augur that the recipient is going to walk out of your life.
Belief in fengshui is pervasive, and keeps a large number of geomancers and
fortune tellers in considerable wealth. The imposing Bank of China
headquarters caused consternation when it was completed in 1988: its mirror
walls reflected angry spirits into many surrounding buildings. A tree had to
be planted in the Governor's garden nearby to prevent evil spirits being
reflected into his house (given the governor's recent untimely resignation,
one might wonder whether the tree was wholly effective).
There was much consternation during the early 1980s, when the Hongkong &amp;
Shanghai banking corporation headquarters was being rebuilt. Their site in
Queen's Road, Central, is at a particularly auspicious junction of positive
natural forces, and the dispersal of staff to temporary offices around the
city was seen as terrible for the bank, and for the territory as a whole.
Worse still, the two bronze guardian lions at the entrance to the bank had
to be kept in storage, laying the territory exposed to any number of
unauspicious forces. No wonder, then, that Hong Kong went through one of the
most turbulent periods of its history during the early 1980s, with currency
crises, bank collapses, and two years of tempestuous negotiation between
Britain and China over its future beyond 1997. It was not just conservative
Chinese who sighed a relief when the new headquarters were completed, and
the lions back on guard.
At a more mundane level, fengshui dictates how a room or office should be
furnished. Many a Columbia educated Chinese graduate has been discovered
realigning desks and chairs in his or her office, putting mirrors up, or
placing a fish tank in a particular position, after advice from a geomancer.
even if they are sceptical about fengshui, pragmatism tells them it is best
to hedge bets.
The forces of yin (the female or cooling principle) and yang (the male, or
heating principle) also play a subtle part in Chinese lives, and should
always be kept in balance. For a visitor, they come into play most clearly
around the dining table, where 'heating' foods like red meat should always
be counterbalanced by 'cooling' foods like fish or vegetables. Guinness or
brandy are yang, while gin or white wine are yin. Fried foods are yang;
poached are yin. It is not just chopsticks one has to wrestle with at the
dining table.
In fact, it is probably at the dining table that the tables are turned on
Chinese who regard westerners as uncouth or barbarian: Chinese table manners
can be shocking to western sensibilities. They may burp and belch; they may
slurp soup or tea with great gusto; they may spit shell and other inedibles
onto the tablecloth by the plate. They may conduct elaborate explorations
with toothpicks. After a chinese meal, a tablecloth is as likely as not to
look like a battlefield.
No offence is meant by any of this. Also, do not be discomfited if the host
serves you personally. It is seen as natural politeness, and need not be
reciprocated. You should try not to use personal chopsticks in the central
serving bowls - this is seen as unhygienic. Also, do not be surprised if a
host draws proceedings quickly to a close once the final course has been
consumed. It is not a Chinese habit to dally at the table after eating  -
perhaps not surprising, giving the mess it may be in.
After making such a meal of the idiosyncracies of Chinese culture, it is
perhaps worth re-emphasising that few people are as cosmopolitan as Hong
Kong Chinese. They are highly tolerant of different cultural habits, and
will tend not to take offence if you are ignorant of theirs. Many are so
westernised that their sensibilities are very similar to our own. Few could
be easier to do business with.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI Photograph Hardly junk food, executives enjoy Chinese cuisine
offshore (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-8012</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBTBGAADFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (6): Paradise for hagglers
 -SHOPPING: bargains about, but haggling in Hong Kong has been refined to an
art form in which most western shoppers are timorous amateurs. says David
Dodwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PETITE, and well-dressed Chinese woman picked up a linen embroidered
tablecloth in a bustling store on Kowloon's Granville Road, and gestured to
the shopkeeper asking a price. After a long preamble describing the fineness
of the work, and the hundreds of hours spent on it by needleworkers in
Suzhou, he confided it would cost about HKDollars 6,000.
There followed much sucking of teeth, accompanied by gestures of disbelief,
and many minutes of commentary about how many shops sell such tablecloths,
and how cheaply they are made in China.
In the minutes that followed, the mysterious rituals of haggling unfolded.
Voices were never raised. There was much smiling and laughing. There were
many restatements of honourability, good faith and being a good customer.
Promises were made about bringing more business to the shop by getting
friends to come. There were inquiries about a better price if she bought
two. Emphasis was placed on the fact she could pay in cash.
It all took half an hour. Both seemed happy as a deal was sealed and the
cloth gift-wrapped  - though the shopkeeper made occasional protests of how
much money he was losing. When she emerged, she had in fact paid HKDollars
1,250.
Haggling in Hong Kong has been refined to an art form in which most western
shoppers are timorous amateurs. While certain shops stick to fixed prices,
haggling is taken for granted in most of them, and most western shoppers
miss out on the sport that for many Hong Kongers appears to be the principle
point of any purchase: it is the travelling, rather than the arriving, that
makes it all worthwhile.
While the example of the tablecloth is real, it is rare in the width of the
chasm that was breached by shopper and shopkeeper. I suspect she had an
inkling of how much the shopkeeper had paid. It is nevertheless not rare for
a realistic sale price to be half the marked price of any item, whether it
is a stereo system or Gameboy, silk flowers or a piece of Paris fashion.
Two important starting points ahead of a serious haggling session are to
know what price you would have to pay for the same thing back home -
including any tax the customs and excise might put on it as you try to slip
inconspicuously through the green channel  - and to be willing to walk away.
Once a shopkeeper scents your reluctance to walk away, he has an upper hand
that you are unlikely to overcome.
Other points to keep in mind are:
Anything you set your eyes on in a street market might be fake, or stolen.
The most obvious fakes are the Rolexes touted from folding tables in street
markets like Temple Street in Kowloon.
'But this isn't a real Rolex,' a friend once protested as he weighed the
offering in his hand. 'No,' replied the tout without embarrassment or
hesitation: 'But real Seiko inside.'
American Express cards are next to useless in the territory, claim some
observers. Hong Kong shopkeepers hate the delay in payment, and the fee they
have to pay, and will add at least six per cent to the price, even if a deal
has ostensibly been sealed.
While Hong Kong is not the bargain basement it once claimed to be, (for best
prices, a shopper must nowadays be in Bangkok), there are still good reasons
to shop here in earnest.
As for electronic goods, the territory is among the first in the world to
get its hands on new Japanese gizmos. You can be sure to find models in Hong
Kong which are unlikely to arrive in shops back home for a year or two. This
applies as much to cameras and camcorders as it does to personal organisers
or portable compact disc players.
Many factory outlets offer haute couture fashions at prices that would
inflame trend-setting purchasers in Paris or Rome. This happens because
quota limits for various countries often prevent the export of everything
made for the big name fashion houses in Europe or the US. Factory outlets
are dotted all over Hong Kong and Kowloon, and are listed in a booklet
published by the Hong Kong Tourist Association, (see section on key facts
for visitors).
Leather goods, most made in mainland China, are beginning to be well styled,
and cost a fraction of leather goods in Europe.
Chinese arts and crafts are more difficult to guage. Prices are likely to be
lower than in tourist outlets in mainland China, and the range of products
available is unlikely to be matched elsewhere. But the territory provides a
convenient hunting ground for many of the world's most expert and most avid
collectors of Chinese arts  - and prices reflect this. Bargains can
undoubtedly be found in areas like Holloway Road above Central, but it will
take luck, patience, and a very good eye to trip over them.
Myth has it that men should have suits tailored in Hong Kong. Needless to
say, in 1986, the FT conducted a straw poll of 'best dressed men' in Hong
Kong only to discover they all had their suits made elsewhere. Italy and
London seemed then to be the preferred locations. It is nevertheless true
that good suits can be made in the territory. Hotel concierges are probably
the best source of tips on where to go. They are likely to be cheaper than
from Savile Row, and if you either offer a suit you already own to be
copied, or have the patience to have at least three fittings, money could
well be saved.
Perhaps the most daunting prospect for any newly-arrived shopper is to
choose the direction in which to point. One can be forgiven for feeling the
territory is wall-to-wall shops. At one end of the spectrum are modern,
luxurious air-conditioned plazas full of Guccis and Ferragamos, and charging
prices similar to those in Paris. These seem to be frequented mostly by
Japanese tourists. At the other end of the spectrum are sweltering outdoor
night markets with a powerful barrow-boy bustle about them.
Air-conditioned shopping is practically well essential in the day time in
summer. On Hong Kong island, the new Pacific Place is impressive, as is the
nearby cobweb of Japanese department stores. In Kowloon, Harbour City and
Ocean Terminal next to the Star Ferry offer miles of fascinating shopping,
while the newly-opened Hong Kong Place in east Tsimshatsui claims to be the
largest shopping complex in Asia.
Out of doors, the liveliest single market is Temple Street in Mong Kok,
which comes alive around seven in the evening, and goes on to midnight.
Stanley Market on the south of Hong Kong island has lots of casual wear in
western sizes. In Central, the tightly packed streets above Queen's Road  -
like Li Yuen streets east and west  - offer handbags, scarves, sweaters,
dresses, toys and imitation jewellery.
The jade market in Kowloon is a popular destination, while the quest for
handicrafts and fine art is concentrated on Holloway Road, Cat Street and
Stanley Main Street. Chinese Arts and Crafts emporiums, owned by mainland
Chinese, are dotted around the territory, and offer an immense range of
goods from across the border.
While Hong Kong is without question a haggler's paradise, it is also the
home of 'caveat emptor.' Once bought, an item will only rarely be returnable
to the seller if it is found to be fake or faulty. Shops carrying the Hong
Kong Tourist Association symbol (a red junk in a circle) offer the highest
level of reliability, but 'caveat emptor' remains the watchword of every
sensible shopper in Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
