<DOCNO>FT921-8015</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBTBGAAAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Hong Kong (3): Visitors spoiled for
choice - Hotels: the recent opening of new luxury hotels has triggered a
fierce competitive response from older marble palaces which appear regularly
among the world's top ten hotels and offer every conceivable service, says
David Dodwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Gulf War, and a rush of new luxury hotels opening their doors, have
given Hong Kong hoteliers an unaccustomed taste of the real world in 1991 as
occupancy rates slipped to average 75 per cent.
In Europe or the US, many hoteliers would be cracking champagne bottles if
they achieved such occupancy rates, but in Hong Kong, after years during
which occupancies have averaged close to 90 per cent all year round, this
has been a sobering time. Particularly vulnerable have been the newest
hotels, and those reliant on the much-depressed US rag trade.
The upside for visitors is that room prices have tumbled, allowing a taste
of unalloyed sybaritic luxury for the price of an average motel in Europe or
the US. Nor has it been essential to make bookings months in advance during
the hectic peak of September to December - a hassle that has humbled many a
business traveller in recent years if he was rash enough to fly in convinced
he would find something on the night.
It is often difficult for a business traveller brutalised by the experience
of hotels in Europe or the US to anticipate the cossetting that can be
assured in any one of 30 of the territory's 81 leading hotels. These marble
palaces (heaven knows how many thousands of acres of marble are shipped into
the territory every year) house every conceivable service - from meals 24
hours a day to laser disc players, and fax machines in your room with your
own personal number.
Even Hong Kong's stateliest and most traditional hotels, like the Peninsula
with four staff to every guest, are awash with the latest electronic gismos
that swish curtains open and closed, dim lights in every nook, pull
satellite channels onto the television screen, bring messages onto the
screen overriding whatever programme you are watching, and activate
personalised answering machines on your room telephone.
A decade ago, choice of the right hotel in Hong Kong was a comparatively
simple affair. If you were visiting bankers, brokers or government officials
your chairman or chief executive stayed at the Mandarin Oriental on Hong
Kong island. Other executives would stay at the Hilton nearby. If you were
in town to visit industry - whether garments or electronics - your chairman
or chief executive stayed at the Peninsula or the Regent on Kowloon side.
Lesser mortals stayed at one of the three Omni hotels near the Star ferry,
or at the Shangri-la, or a neighbour on the east Tsinshatsui waterfront.
All of these hotels appeared regularly among the world's top ten hotels, so
even the middle-ranking executive could be assured of uncommon luxury. The
only problem was booking a room in the first place.
Today, choice is a more perplexing affair. For traditionalists, perhaps
there will never be an alternative to the Mandarin, the Peninsula or the
Regent. But arriviste hotels like the Grand Hyatt, the Conrad and the Island
Shangri-la (all on Hong Kong island) and the Ramada Renaissance and Hotel
Nikko in Kowloon can offer services that match, and often better, the
territory's grand dame hotels, which must make do, of course, with
comparatively older property.
The biggest single new influence has been the opening two years ago of Hong
Kong's massive Convention and Exhibition centre on the Wanchai waterfront on
Hong Kong island. The centre itself houses two hotels - the Grand Hyatt and
the New World Harbour View  - with three others at nearby Pacific Place. As
the volume of conference and exhibition business grows in Hong Kong, so an
increasing number of visitors are likely to shun the hotels of Kowloon and
Central, staying instead at one of the five hotels closest by.
It is not the Convention Centre alone that will draw visitors away from
traditional haunts. The Grand Hyatt has flooded the hotel industry with
hype, but has so far offered a quality that lives up to all but its most
extravagant claims - such as that which claims it provides a 'neo-nostalgic
celebration of the sophisticated turn of the century.' But what exactly is
'neo-nostalgia'?
In Pacific Place, a glittering palace to the main Hong Kong religion of
shopping, the Conrad and the Island Shangri-la will compete hard with the
Hyatt for quality and service. The third hotel, the Marriott, feels modest
only when set against the likes of the Grand Hyatt, and anyway has such
strong loyalty from among US visitors that it could well maintain the
highest occupancy rates of the three.
The recent opening of these hotels has triggered a fierce competitive
response from older hotels. In Kowloon, the Regent has refurbished suites,
and enlarged its gymnasium. The Peninsula is pressing ahead with plans to
add a 30-storey extension that will (for the first time) give guests a pool,
a health centre and a business centre.
Perhaps the most vigorous response has come from the Hilton in Hong Kong's
Central district. Having several years ago been the first in the territory
to introduce executive and non-smoking floors, it has launched for Japanese
guests a 'wa no kutsurogi' service that will allow them to be checked in on
their own floor by Japanese-speaking hotel staff, with all hotel room
literature in Japanese.
A new 'Meetings 2000' service is intended to meet all the high-tech needs of
executives wanting to use the hotel as a base for presentations or other
functions. It is aimed at warding off fierce competition from hotels like
the Conrad, which has a 54-seat lecture theatre along with usual business
centre and meeting rooms, and the Island Shangri-la, which has a genteel
library as well as state of the art meeting rooms in its expansive business
centre. Such new hotels offer extensive in-room facilities like data lines
for computers and faxes, and double telephone lines. Nevertheless, for sheer
value for money, the Hilton is hard to beat.
A second recent development has been the appearance of a host of excellent
three- and four-star hotels aimed at tour groups, and visitors with more
limited budgets, many from Taiwan, south east Asia, and even China. A total
of seven opened in 1991, with a further nine expected to open this year.
Perhaps the most ambitious is the 1,000-room Panda Hotel in the outlying
area of Tsuen Wan, which may rely heavily on visitors from mainland China
and Taiwan. The 500-room Century hotel in Wanchai is certain to attract
budget-conscious overspill from the Convention Centre. It opened only a
couple of months ago, but has attracted favourable mention so far.
Help in picking the right hotel is hard to give, such is the luxury of
choice and the wide range of executive services offered by so many hotels.
Hong Kong's roads nevertheless become increasingly congested  - particularly
around the main harbour crossing  - so an increasingly sensible rule of
thumb is to pick a hotel close to the venue of most meetings.
Idiosyncratic needs are easier to meet:
Transiting overnight  - stay at the Regal Airport hotel.
Keen on jogging  - stay at the Regent on Kowloon-side, to jog along the
Tsinshatsui waterfront, or the Hilton, Island Shangri-la or Conrad on the
island, since these give good access to Bowen Road, one of the world's most
panoramic jogs.
Keen on swimming  - most hotels have excellent pools. However, the Mandarin
pool is a marble-lined puddle, and the Peninsula has none, so sybaritic are
its guests.
Keen on squash  - the Ramada Renaissance in Kowloon has a good court.
Afraid of heights  - stay with traditional stalwarts like the Mandarin, the
Hilton or the Peninsula. Many hotels make the most of spectacular views, so
you may need to carry sweets in a pocket to help your ears 'pop' as you leap
past the 50th floor.
