<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / International Company News: Manpower cuts losses in fourth
quarter to Dollars 20m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANPOWER, the temporary employment business which was taken over by
Britain's Blue Arrow but has now redomiciled in the US, yesterday reported a
fourth-quarter net loss of Dollars 20m, down from a loss of Dollars 60.2m in
the same period of last year.
The figures included Dollars 19.5m of goodwill amortisation and Dollars 10m
of restructuring charges compared with Dollars 20.1m and Dollars 51.5m
respectively in the same period of 1990.
After-tax earnings, excluding amortisation and restructuring, came to
Dollars 9.5m, down 16.2 per cent from the Dollars 11.3m of 1990. Corporate
revenues were Dollars 709m, down from Dollars 766m.
For the full year, earnings excluding amortisation and special charges
totalled Dollars 29.4m, down 50 per cent from 1990's Dollars 59.6m.
Mr Mitchell Fromstein, president, said the 1991 results reflected severe US
and UK recession in the first half and a modest US recovery in the second
half.
The company felt the worst was behind it, in that sales levels compared with
the previous year had improved modestly but continuously since mid-summer
and it expected the trend to continue for the first quarter of 1992.
</TEXT>
