<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Del Monte Foods poised for flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEL MONTE Foods Interna-tional, the processed fruit manufacturer, is
preparing for a Pounds 450m flotation on the London stock market.
The share sale will be one of the biggest non-privatisation flotations for
several years. It will make multi-millionaires of the company's four
executive directors, who together bought 5 per cent of its shares in a
management buy-out in May 1990.
DMFI is completely separate from the Del Monte fresh fruit business, which
was bought by Polly Peck, the fruit and electronics conglomerate that
collapsed in 1990. Polly Peck's administrators are also thought to be
planning to float their Del Monte business, although probably in the US.
Both companies were for many years part of RJR Nabisco, the US food and
tobacco group.
When Nabisco was bought by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the US buy-out
specialists, in February 1989, Del Monte was sold and broken up.
DMFI has exclusive rights to use the Del Monte name for processed foods in
most parts of the world except the US. Its biggest market is Italy, where
its annual sales are Pounds 80m, followed by the UK, where the turnover is
Pounds 70m.
While other big buy-outs in the past couple of years have struggled to hit
their financial targets, DMFI's profits have grown rapidly. In the year to
November 1991, profits before interest and tax rose 24 per cent to Pounds
29.5m, as sales grew 13 per cent to Pounds 252m.
'No business is recession proof,' said Mr Leon Allen, chairman. 'However, we
have succeeded in pushing up both the volume of sales, by 10 per cent last
year, and in widening margins.' The company is confident of at least
maintaining its profit and sales growth.
The business is being floated by Charterhouse, the merchant bank whose
investment funds own half of DMFI, and Cazenove, the stockbrokers.
The share sale is scheduled for the autumn. There will be a London listing
although many of the shares will be offered to institutions in Europe.
Between Pounds 250m and Pounds 300m of shares will be offered to individuals
and institutions, with existing shareholders keeping the rest.
Of the shares being sold, about Pounds 200m will be new equity to redeem
preference shares and pay off debt.
</TEXT>
