<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Virgin Atlantic incurs Pounds 9m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Richard Branson's Virgin Atlantic Airways lost Pounds 9m before tax last
year on its continuing businesses according to its previously unpublished
financial results.
Voyager Holdings, the private holding company for the airline and its tour
operator, is looking to raise Pounds 55m by selling a 20 per cent stake.
Its search for partners, at the same time as Mr Branson's negotiations to
sell Virgin Music Group, his record company, for a reported Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 570m), has prompted speculation that the airline needs cash
urgently.
The airline's results show it did not escape recession and intense price
competition with British Airways and other transatlantic rivals, but its
debts did not rise precipitously last year, contrary to industry comments.
Mr Branson, last said: 'We don't need cash at all if the airline were to
trade just with the routes it has now. But it is a cheap time to expand, and
we like to bring in partners before we need them.'
He added: 'Even if we do the music deal, we've gone a fair way with the
airline placing and we'll probably go ahead anyway.'
Virgin is marketing the airline stake - through Salomon Brothers, the US
investment bank - against the backdrop of severe recession throughout the
airline industry worldwide.
Voyager's pre-tax profits slumped to just Pounds 775,000 in the year to July
1991 from Pounds 8.5m in 1989-90 as the Gulf war pushed up fuel costs and
deterred potential passengers.
Although the airline saw turnover leap to Pounds 248.3m from Pounds 180.5m
as it started flights to Boston and added flights to Tokyo, it made a Pounds
3m pre-tax loss - compared with a Pounds 7.3m profit the year before - after
taking a Pounds 6m book profit on selling one of its 747 aircraft.
Virgin Atlantic started flying out of Heathrow in July 1991, launching a
battle for market share with British Airways.
The year to July bore the heavy start-up costs of the new routes,
particularly six months advance training of crews, but received none of the
revenue.
In spite of the recession, Virgin Atlantic maintained its policy of low
fares and add-on incentives, which squeezed profits.
The airline losses were partly offset by Virgin Holidays, the tour operator,
which more than doubled its profits to Pounds 3.3m.
</TEXT>
