<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Britain and France may fund new fighter project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE and Dassault Aviation of France expect to receive funding
from their governments to study co-operation on a future generation of
fighter aircraft.
The companies have been discussing possible collaboration for about two
years, it emerged yesterday.
A senior Dassault executive said: 'In the coming months we will make joint
proposals to our two governments to secure study contracts so that we can
prepare for the future together.'
Revival of Anglo-French co-operation would not affect the two fighter jets
in which the companies are separately involved, the European Fighter
Aircraft (EFA) and the Rafale. Both are due to be in service in the late
1990s.
France took part in the early stages of the EFA project before breaking off
in 1985 because of different requirements and arguments about project
leadership. This left the UK to develop the Dollars 20bn-plus EFA with
Germany, Italy and Spain. France is developing the lighter-weight Rafale on
its own. A new generation is not expected before 2020.
The renewed contacts are believed to have been instigated by the French and
British defence ministries in the belief that Europe cannot afford more than
one project.
BAe said it had been holding talks with Dassault on 'specific technologies'.
These 'could be applied to some future project beyond EFA and Rafale in line
with the wishes of both governments for closer industrial co-operation in
the defence field'.
It added that it was also discussing sharing technologies with McDonnell
Douglas of the US, its partner in the Harrier II jump-jet, and Saab-Scania
of Sweden.
Dassault made clear that its co-operation with BAe could be extended to
other European companies.
Deutsche Aerospace, a partner of BAe in EFA, wants to use the EFA consortium
as the basis for forming a combined European military aircraft group which
could eventually bring in Dassault.
Prospects for Dassault continuing on its own have dwindled in recent years
as its military aircraft exports have dried up and the French government has
cut equipment spending.
</TEXT>
