<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Kinnock scoffs at Majorism - Prime
Minister's questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN would face 'perma-nent high unemployment' if the general election
resulted in a fourth successive Conservative victory, Mr Neil Kinnock said
in the Commons yesterday.
With Labour's hopes of pulling ahead in the opinion polls now resting on the
depth of the recession, the Labour leader seized on the latest figures
showing a rise in the number of long-term unemployed to charge that the
government had to bear the blame. During another angry exchange at prime
minister's questions, he insisted: 'Majorism is not working.'
Labour will return to the theme later today, when Mr John Smith, shadow
chancellor, opens a full-scale Commons debate on the effect of the recession
on manufacturing industry.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said: 'The only way of getting these
figures down permanently is to have the right structure of development
within the economy - low inflation and stable exchange rates.' Government
policies were designed to achieve these objectives, while Labour policies
would lead to 'permanent slump - no jobs, no prospects, no hope for the
future'.
Mr Kinnock sought to associate the prime minister directly with the view of
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, that rising unemployment and the recession
had been the price 'well worth paying' to get inflation down. Mr Major
retorted: 'I have said no such thing and neither, in context, has the
chancellor.'
This denial brought furious protests from Labour with Mr Robin Corbett, MP
for Birmingham Erdington, recalling the occasion in May when Mr Lamont first
referred to the price 'well worth paying'. Downing Street later emphasised
that in correcting what it called a misquotation the prime minister had not
sought to distance himself from the chancellor.
In the Commons exchanges Mr Major argued that if Mr Kinnock was really
concerned about unemployment he would not be advocating policies which would
'cripple' industry. These included bringing back flying pickets and
restoring the legal immunities of unions 'with all the difficulties we saw
in the 1960s and 1970s'.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, said the government's commitment
to recovery could best be judged by the fact that last week's announcement
of a 53,000 increase in unemployment had been followed by a Pounds 171m cut
in the training budget. Mr Major stressed that the provision for training
was the highest Britain had ever known.
He cited the Bundesbank's statement that Germany was now in recession as
further evidence that Britain's current difficulties had not been caused by
government policies.
</TEXT>
