<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Old guard on the retreat in many Labour town halls: Policy
shifts by some of the party's top local politicians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALMOST ALL the 57 urban areas eligible to compete for the Pounds 750m of
City Challenge funding announced yesterday have Labour councils.
Predictably, they joined Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, in
denouncing the competition as a 'game show pandering to the whims and
prejudices of an egocentric environment secretary'.
They will play the game all the same - with enthusiasm, in many cases. In
last year's competition, Manchester won cash for renovating its shabby Hulme
district south of the city centre. Mr Graham Stringer, Labour leader of the
city council, opposes the bidding element in City Challenge but declares
himself 'far from cynical' about the process of preparing bids.
'It has brought together government, council, tenants, businesses, churches
and voluntary bodies to help find a common solution to our urban problems',
he says. 'If Labour wins the general election we need to keep that process.
The contacts made are lasting.'
It is a typical response. The crusading socialism of the early 1980s is
little in evidence among today's generation of Labour council chiefs.
Leading lights such as Mr Stringer and Ms Margaret Hodge in north London's
Islington, once heroes of the hard left, are arch-pragmatists now. Others,
such as Mr Jeremy Beecham in Newcastle upon Tyne, were Kinnockite 'soft
left' from the start.
'The old left/right divide is obsolete,' says Mr Rod Hills, Labour leader of
York City Council. 'Now the division is generational, between innovators and
an old guard.' If Labour wins the election, much more than City Challenge
will depend on the respective influence of those two groups.
Both are largely united on five priorities: creation of single-tier
all-purpose authorities; the return of the fixing of business rate to
councils; a general power of competence for councils to act - and spend - as
they see fit; abolition of compulsory competitive tendering; and freeing of
councils' accumulated capital receipts for them to spend on housing and
other programmes.
Ms Janet Silet, leader of Norwich City Council, says: 'If they release part
of our Pounds 30m in capital reserves, we will start a house-building
programme the next day. We have sites designated and already have planning
permission.' Mr Gould has warned councils that Labour would relax spending
constraints 'progressively'. The rate of progress is likely to cause
tension.
Mr Gould is also committed to abolishing the compulsory aspect of tendering,
a process that highlights the gulf between the innovators and the old guard.
The old guard simply wants to be free of it and, like most of the
local-government trade unions, hankers for the old days in which work was
done automatically by councils' own labour forces. By contrast, the
innovators are keen to retain - and even extend - the cost centres, service
plans and quality targets that have been part of the competitive-tendering
process.
Mr Stringer, who is pressing ahead with service plans for every council
department in Manchester, says: 'Targets and effective monitoring are
crucial. It's amazing that local authorities often don't even know how many
they employ, let alone what they do.'
Under Mr Hills, York has pioneered a local citizen's charter, customer
contracts and annual performance indicators - seen as a models of their
kind. He supports Labour's proposed quality commission as a means of
spreading best practice, and favours it intervening in badly run
authorities.
Among innovators, partnership is the vogue word. It underpins a growing
commitment to community politics on the one hand, and the European Community
on the other. 'When I go to Brussels,' says Mr Stringer, 'I get a much
friendlier reception than in Whitehall these days.'
Radical attitudes to constitutional change are also evident. Support for
regional government, electoral reform and coalition politics is strong and
spreading among Labour councillors. Mr Stringer believes most councillors
back proportional representation. In Manchester, he says, 'we get 55 per
cent of the vote and 86 per cent of the seats - not an obvious recipe for
good government.'
Ms Hodge thinks on the same lines. As the most likely leader of Labour's
proposed Greater London Authority, which would be elected by PR, she may
soon be setting the tone for the rest.
</TEXT>
