<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Limited scope seen for Whitehall agencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE of the limited scope for government agencies to improve their
business performance is disclosed today in the National Audit Office's first
report on an executive agency.
The report by the government expenditure watchdog examines the Vehicle
Inspectorate, which tests heavy-goods vehicles and public-service vehicles,
supervises the annual MoT tests for cars and enforces some driver and
vehicle legislation.
The inspectorate was the first executive agency set up under the Next Steps
initiative launched in 1988 to create arm's-length agencies to deliver
government services.
The NAO says the inspectorate has become significantly more efficient since
it became an executive agency in 1988. Between 1989 and 1991, efficiency
savings reached 8.8 per cent of costs compared with the government's target
of 3.7 per cent.
But scope for further improvements is limited by government policy, the NAO
says. The Vehicle Inspectorate is not free to close under-used testing
stations, some of which operate for only a few days a week. Moreover,
Treasury rules limit the discretion of agencies to compete with the private
sector for additional work.
These limitations are 'a useful illustration of the differences between an
executive agency and a market-led business', the report concludes.
'If the inspectorate were acting as a market-led business, they would now be
looking more radically at the resources they have and the services they
provide,' it says. 'For example, a business would be considering whether to
rationalise under-utilised assets or whether to seek new business that would
use assets more fully.'
The NAO finds that the inspectorate has become more responsive to the needs
of its customers since becoming an agency. According to a Mori opinion poll
conducted for the NAO last year, 40 per cent of customers considered that
the quality of service had improved since 1988 while 91 per cent considered
that the overall service was very or fairly good. Customer service
initiatives launched by the Vehicle Inspectorate since it became an agency
are evidence of a determination to improve services, the NAO says. But
success of the initiatives - which include Saturday testing and the sale of
technical publications - has been mixed because no detailed market research
or cost-benefit analysis was carried out.
The NAO says there are still some practical improvements which can be made
to the inspectorate's running. These include putting measures of quality in
targets and greater devolution of management responsibilities to district
offices.
The Vehicle Inspectorate, HMSO. Pounds 7.10.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
