<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Warning over results in school 'league tables'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLICATION of school examination results in 'league tables' can be
seriously misleading if made without an estimate of 'added value', according
to a paper published by the National Commission for Education.
The paper, by Professor Andrew McPherson of Edinburgh University, calls for
'raw results' of tests and exams published by the government and local
authorities to be accompanied by an assessment of the contribution a school
makes to its pupils' progress. This should take account of each pupil's
prior level of attainment and other factors influencing progress.
The paper is the first to be published by the commission, a privately funded
body conducting an in-depth inquiry into Britain's education system.
The National Association of Head Teachers will seek a High Court injunction
tomorrow to prevent the governors of Stratford School in east London from
impeding the headteacher in the running of the school.
NEC Briefing No. 1, National Commission on Education, Suite 24, 10-18 Manor
Gardens, London N7 6JY. Free.
Parliament, Page 11
</TEXT>
