<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / BTG sell-off likely to see only two bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY TWO buyers for the British Technology Group are likely to be left in
the field when the government's final deadline for bids expires tomorrow.
They are a consortium led by the BTG management and a British-American group
headed by Mr John Ashworth, director of the London School of Economics.
A third consortium headed by Sir Ronald Mason, former chief scientist at the
Ministry of Defence, and Mr Peter Homer of James Finlay Bank in Glasgow
pulled out of the controversial privatisation of the state-owned technology
transfer group last night.
'The tortuous, changing and time-limited procedures have now prevented us
from bringing together sufficient funds to support the grouping of
investors, universities and research organisations as envisaged in our
plans,' Sir Ronald said.
Mr Homer blamed the Department of Trade and Industry and its financial
adviser, Price Waterhouse, for 'withholding key information on BTG'.
Under the complex rules of the BTG sell-off, only consortia with at least
seven members may submit bids.
The BTG management consortium and Mr John Ashworth's Anglo-American group
say they will definitely bid. The latter includes Research Corporation
Technologies, the leading US technology-transfer organisation and BTG's
closest competitor. Neither consortium will reveal its other members.
There is still an outside chance of a bid from a group led by Strategy
International, a London consultancy. The company refused to comment
yesterday on its plans.
Other bidders have condemned the process for what they claim is unnecessary
secrecy and confusion about the criteria on which submissions will be
judged. Price is important - although bids are unlikely to exceed Pounds 50m
 -and so is long-term commitment to BTG's business of commercialising
university research.
The government hopes to complete the sale next month, so that it will not be
affected by a general election in April.
</TEXT>
