<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Hard line urged on directors' liability for accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES' ACCOUNTS should contain a statement of directors'
responsibilities which should be be approved by their auditors, the
Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland said yesterday.
It should state explicitly the legal responsibilities of directors in
preparing the accounts, which includes the requirement that the figures give
a 'true and fair view'. They should also give details of the maintenance and
effectiveness of internal financial controls.
The recommendations are based on a study conducted by a working party
established by the institute in April last year to examine issues of
corporate governance. It calls for the widespread adoption of audit
committees by companies and the strengthening of internal financial
controls.
Auditors are already legally obliged to highlight any directors' statements
they disagree with in the annual report. The recommendation for a more
detailed directors' report - which should not be a pro forma statement -
would strengthen auditors' powers to comment on a company's internal
controls.
Mr Ian Tegner, institute president, said that an audited directors'
statement would represent a move towards a more detailed, 'qualitative' form
of financial reporting, in that auditors would verify the content of the
statement as well as the figures in the company's accounts.
He added that a significant aim was to confront boards of directors with
their responsibilities and get them to take them seriously.
The institute argues that any additional costs incurred by auditors
scrutinising the directors' statements should be balanced by efficiency
gains resulting from improved internal controls.
The report has been submitted to the Cadbury committee on corporate
governance, which is expected to report in the next few months.
The report also echoes proposals now before the Auditing Practices Board,
which sets standards, for an expanded audit statement which would list the
responsibilities of directors.
Corporate Governance. Directors' Responsibilities For Financial Statements.
ICAS, 27 Queen St, Edinburgh EH2 1LA. Pounds 5
</TEXT>
