<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Deprivation linked to increase in crime rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Metropolitan Police yesterday identified a 'social and economic malaise'
as a factor in record crime rates in London, Alan Pike writes.
Commander David Stevens, presenting the capital's crime trends for last
year, said the figures had to be viewed against the background of the
recession. A 26 per cent increase in street crime last year had occurred
largely in areas of social depriva-tion.
The pre-election atmosphere, said Commander Stevens, was an opportune one
for the community to influence policing.
Recorded crime in London rose 11 per cent to a record 926,200 offences last
year, and national figures are expected to show a similar trend.
The link between social deprivation and crime is not one which that appeals
to ministers, who denied that deprivation caused the recent Tyneside riots.
Mr Roy Hattersley, shadow home secretary, said the figures highlighted the
government's failure to tackle the causes of crime rather than its symptoms.
</TEXT>
