<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Irish abortion ruling plunges PM into crisis: Reynolds to
hold cross-party talks today to seek consensus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER just one week in office Mr Albert Reynolds, Ireland's new prime
minister, has run headlong into a constitutional crisis over a High Court
ruling on Monday prohibiting a 14-year-old girl, allegedly raped, from
obtaining an abortion in the UK.
Opposition leaders were yesterday sharply critical of Mr Reynolds' new
attorney-general for having sought the High Court injunction against the
girl.
Mr John Bruton, leader of the Fine Gael party, said the ruling had 'created
an atmosphere of trauma, fear and uncertainty and may lead both to a failure
to report (rape) and a significantly greater incidence of abortion than
would otherwise occur'.
Mr Proinsias de Rossa, the Workers' party leader, said an appalling legal
precedent had been created which would haunt every Irish woman and girl.
'The attorney-general has displayed an appalling lack of sensitivity and
judgment'.
Mr Bobbie Molloy, a senior member of the cabinet and one of six deputies
from the Progressive Democrat (PD) party on whom Mr Reynolds' Fianna Fail
party rely for support in the coalition government, said his party favoured
the abortion issue going to a referendum.
Mr Reynolds, who has five daughters, is to meet opposition leaders later
today in an effort to obtain cross-party agreement on the issue. He said it
was a tragic and distressing case of unique constitutional and 'humanitarian
importance' but went on to defend his attorney-general saying: 'I do not
believe the people of this country want or deserve a situation of nods and
winks in the application of the law. . . in the long run it would do great
harm to our country'.
Abortion is illegal under Irish law and, following a 1983 amendment to the
constitution, the state is obliged to guarantee the right to life of the
unborn, although it must also pay 'due regard to the equal right to life of
the mother'.
The anti-abortion legislation, strengthened by the High Court ruling, could
face a possible challenge through the European Court for its implications in
limiting the free movement of Irish women within the EC  - which would
contravene the Treaty of Rome - and as an issue of basic human rights.
It is estimated that several thousand Irish women have abortions in the UK
every year. They face prison sentences if found out.
</TEXT>
