<PROFILE>_AN-CBSB3ADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Setback for Bush as challenger beats poll hopes: Tsongas
takes New Hampshire lead for Democratic nomination
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANCHESTER, NEW HAMPSHIRE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush suffered a serious setback to his re-election campaign
early today after a surprisingly strong showing by Mr Patrick Buchanan, his
right-wing challenger for the Republican party's nomination, in voting in
New Hampshire.
Exit polls indicated a narrow victory for Mr Bush, with Mr Buchanan likely
to capture more than 40 per cent of the votes in the republican primary
election in the state.
In the race for the Democratic party's nomination, former Massachusetts
Senator Paul Tsongas was heading for victory, with Governor Bill Clinton of
Arkansas expected to run a strong second.
New Hampshire was the first real test of the strength for candidates seeking
party endorsement for the US presidential election in November. The
conservative eastern state has a tradition of political upsets and voting
yesterday was no exception.
Republicans and independents in the state appeared determined - through the
Republican primary - to register a protest vote against Mr Bush, who has
come under fierce attack for failing to deal with the recession-hit economy
in the New England region.
Mr Buchanan's powerful showing would easily allow him to continue his
campaign, increasing the impression that Mr Bush is vulnerable in the
November election.
Mr Buchanan, a television commentator and former speech writer to Presidents
Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan, appeared to have swung large blocks of
Republican votes with a platform of tax cuts and an 'America First' message
of protectionism and neo-isolationism.
Mr Buchanan appears ready to continue the fight next month in Georgia, South
Carolina and Texas. For Mr Bush, this raises the danger of a split within
the Republican party.
The White House early today said Mr Bush was delighted with his win and it
blamed his weak showing on the state of the New Hampshire economy. Mr Bush
said he understood 'the message of dissatisfaction' and pledged to campaign
vigorously against Mr Buchanan in the weeks ahead.
But the result was a humiliating one for an incumbent president who only six
months ago appeared invincible.
Most observers said the president needed a two-to-one margin to stave off
the challenge from Mr Buchanan who launched his campaign only ten days ago.
The unexpected Republican result threatens to overshadow the Democratic
results, which showed Mr Tsongas performing less well than expected.
Mr Tsongas, a pro-business liberal, has become an unlikely front-runner for
Democratic nomination. But leading Democrats have questioned his appeal
beyond his regional base and he needed a solid win to deter other candidates
from entering the race.
Exit polls suggested that Mr Clinton, coming a close second, had overcome
damage caused by unsubstantiated charges of adultery and draft dodging
during the Vietnam war.
Mr Clinton said early today: 'New Hampshire has made Bill Clinton the
comeback kid.'
The battle for third place in the Democratic race appeared tight between
Senator Robert Kerrey of Nebraska and Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa. Both
needed at least a third place to continue their campaign.
