<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Maxwell lawyers risk clash with MPs by keeping silent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAWYERS acting for Mr Kevin Maxwell and his brother Ian have risked a
confrontation with MPs by again refusing to answer questions sent by the
House of Commons committee investigating the raiding of Maxwell companies'
pension funds.
In a letter to the social security committee, lawyers for the brothers have
refused to allow even written responses to the MPs' questionnaire, in spite
of earlier indications that they might break their silence.
Their decision could prompt MPs to call for a full debate on the Maxwells'
apparent defiance of parliament's authority - although many MPs may be
anxious to avoid political rows so close to the general election.
Last month, when the brothers appeared before the committee, their lawyers
said they had a 'a precious constitutional right and a historic one' to
remain silent.
The Maxwells' lawyers have repeatedly referred to the possibility of their
clients facing legal action over the conduct of companies controlled by the
late Mr Robert Maxwell, and similar arguments are believed to have been used
in their letter to the committee.
They had previously indicated that written answers to the MPs questions
might be possible. However, they suggested guarantees would be required to
ensure that the information would not be made public until the risk of
prejudicing any trial had passed.
The cross-party committee is looking into ways of preventing abuse of
pension funds. It gave trustees of all the Maxwell pension funds, including
the Maxwell brothers, two weeks to reply to 70 questions on the Maxwell
pension fund raids.
The questionnaire asked how much was missing from each pension fund, when
the trustees had become aware it had gone, and how it had disappeared.
Trustees were also asked if they were party to the signing of any transfer
of funds.
About 50 questionnaires were sent out. Most have now been returned and the
responses are expected to be published by the Commons shortly.
The committee, chaired by Mr Frank Field, Labour MP for Birkenhead, will
meet soon to decide its response to the Maxwells' continuing refusal to
answer questions, and whether to recommend further action.
