<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Pressure grows for cut in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, LISA WOOD, EMMA TUCKER and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS FOR an early cut in UK interest rates strengthened yesterday after
the pound firmed and news of a big rise in long-term unemployment increased
pressure on the government to stimulate the economy.
Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of England, also stressed the
potential problems for the UK economy when he warned that the confidence of
exporters could be damaged by a slowdown in the world economy.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton's warnings coincided with news of the increase in
long-term unemployment, which was most marked in the relatively affluent
south-west, south-east and East Anglia.
Sterling rose half a pfennig against a weaker D-Mark to close last night at
DM2.885, its highest level in the European exchange rate mechanism since
mid-December. In New York it held on to its gains to finish at DM2.8855.
The pound's strength encouraged hopes that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor,
could cut borrowing costs while keeping the pound stable within the ERM.
The pressures on Mr Lamont intensified after the Department of Employment
said the numbers out of work for 12 months or more stood at 747,000 in
January, an increase of 93,000 on the previous three months. Long-term
unemployment is at its highest level for three years.
The unemployment figures sparked angry scenes in the House of Commons, where
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour party leader, protested that government policies
were making life a misery for hundreds of thousands of people.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said the figures were 'extremely
unwelcome' but there was 'no easy way' to counter rising unemployment.
Mr Lamont has been urged by Conservative MPs and industrialists to cut
rates, which have been held at 10.5 per cent for more than five months, in
an effort to stimulate the economy ahead of the election. There has been
speculation that he will do so either on or around Budget day on March 10,
possibly along with Budget measures to cut income tax.
The Bank of England is believed to have warned Mr Lamont that cutting rates
might be unsafe when the pound is well below its central ERM limit of
DM2.95.
However, the recent strengthening in the pound - from a low point in early
January of about DM2.83 - may provide the chancellor with the arguments he
needs to justify a cut in borrowing rates of perhaps half a percentage
point.
Sterling was helped by a stronger dollar, which led to more international
funds flowing out of the D-Mark and reduced the strains on the other ERM
currencies.
The dollar closed in London against the D-Mark at its highest level for
three months, at DM1.6480, for a gain of 2 1/2 pfennigs on the day. In New
York it eased to close at DM1.644.
On London money markets, the key three-month interbank rate - which shadows
base rates - eased   1/16 to close at about 10 3/16 per cent.
Speaking at an Engineering Employers' Federation dinner, Mr Leigh-Pemberton
said increased world economic uncertainty could affect export performance -
one of the few bright spots for the UK economy over the past year. In spite
of this, he remained optimistic about a recovery in the second half of the
year.
The Bank governor's fears on exports were reinforced by Sir John Banham,
director general of the Confederation of British Industry. He blamed the
'incessant politicisation' of the economy for hitting consumer confidence.
Back from a three-week tour of UK export markets, he said: 'The further you
get from London the better the UK economy looks. We are too prone to talk
ourselves down and our competitors up.'
The Employment Department said long-term unemployment was about half its
level of five years ago; among 18-24 year-olds it was at its highest since
April 1989, but this was also about half its 1987 level.
The figures showed a sharp rise in the number unemployed for more than six
months, up 136,000 to 1,338,000 in the three months to January.
Overall, the percentage of long-term jobless as a proportion of total
unemployment rose just 1 per cent to 28 per cent during the year.
