<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Nikkei falls as hopes of
interest rate cut recede
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARE PRICES fell on futures-related selling and liquidation of holdings by
investment trust funds, and the Nikkei average shed Monday's 2.1 per cent
gain, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
The 225-issue average closed 452.95 down at 20,872.03, after a day's high of
21,294.02 and low of 20,807.40. An afternoon fall in futures prices had
prompted arbitrage unwinding.
Volume was flat at 200m shares. Declines led advances by 608 to 328, with
177 issues unchanged. The Topix index of all first section stocks lost 19.84
at 1,539.99, and in London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index weakened 15.48 to
1,163.89.
Market participants were disappointed that foreign exchanges had ignored
Monday's intervention by the Bank of Japan and the Federal Reserve Bank of
New York to support the yen against the dollar. The US unit rallied against
European currencies, and rose to Y127.17, up from Y126.93, against the yen.
The rise dampened hopes of lower interest rates and prompted profit-taking
in the equity market.
Tokkin, or specified money trusts, and investment trusts, which face
redemptions, were seen liquidating holdings. However, some analysts believe
the Bank of Japan will ease short-term money rates in the event of a sharp
downturn in the Nikkei. Mr Jason James, strategist at James Capel, said the
bottom range for the index was around 20,000.
Financial issues were lower on small-lot corporate selling ahead of the
March book closing. Industrial Bank of Japan fell Y150 to Y2,680 and Fuji
Bank Y100 to Y2,000.
Steel issues retreated initially on reports of a further decline in crude
steel output for January. Crude steel output fell by a year-on-year 14.8 per
cent last month, the sixth consecutive monthly decline. However, bargain
hunting later supported NKK, which added Y6 at Y331, and Tokyo Steel, which
gained Y20 to Y2,370.
High-priced small-capital issues with low pay-out ratios advanced on hopes
that the companies will raise dividends, or announce stock splits. Keyence,
the measuring equipment maker, climbed Y200 to Y10,700 and Family Mart, the
retailer, put on Y130 to Y8,930.
After the close, Mr Minoru Nagaoka, president of the Tokyo Stock Exchange
(TSE), said the exchange had started an investigation into the recent
trading of shares in Daito Trust Construction. The company, which made a
debut on the TSE's first section on February 5, ran into heavy selling last
week amid rumours that it had guaranteed debt for a bankrupt concern. Daito
ended Y50 off at Y8,550, compared with Y9,780, the closing price on its
first day of trading.
In Osaka, the OSE average slipped 85.74 to 22,556.78 in volume of 52.1m
shares. Window dressing ahead of the March book closing lifted smaller
companies. High-technology shares weakened on worries over earnings.
Roundup
A LOWER Nikkei depressed sentiment in the Pacific Rim, although most bourses
were affected by local issues. Thailand was closed.
HONG KONG, after starting strongly, lost some ground on afternoon
profit-taking. The Hang Seng index finished a net 27.91 up at 4,747.10 in
turnover of HKDollars 1.7bn.
There were rumours of covered warrant issues from Bank of East Asia and
Hopewell: the bank was unchanged at HKDollars 21.40 while the property group
rose 2.50 cents to HKDollars 4.00. Jardine Matheson put on HKDollars 1.00 to
HKDollars 44.50 as sentiment towards trading companies turned positive.
Citic Pacific, the Chinese-backed investment trust, moved ahead 15 cents or
6.6 per cent to HKDollars 2.40 as the Quok family increased its holding.
SEOUL dipped 1.92 to 638.22, with interest in securities shares preventing
the market from falling further. The Korea Securities Market Stabilisation
Fund said it would pay a 5 per cent dividend to members.
JAKARTA retreated, the index closing 4.16 down at 286.75 in volume of 7.6m
shares.
KUALA LUMPUR firmed on hopes that interest rates might be cut, although Bank
Negara, the central bank, has indicated that a reduction might not occur for
another three months. The composite index rose 9.89 to 607.67 in volume of
65m shares (41m). Telekom gained 20 cents to MDollars 11.10, with 1.8m
shares traded.
SINGAPORE retrieved most of Monday's loss. The Straits Times Industrial
index improved 6.99 to 1,501.80 in volume of 58m shares.
TAIWAN fell further on concern over the central bank's decision to restrict
foreign investment. The weighted index lost 92.57 or 1.9 per cent to
4,766.91.
MANILA eased afresh, partly on reports that a family trust wanted to
liquidate part of its holding in Ayala Corporation. The composite index was
2.53 off at 1,176.57.
AUSTRALIA's early gains were trimmed back by the fall in Tokyo. The All
Ordinaries index closed 12.5 up at 1,626.7. News Corp rose 58 cents to a
record high of ADollars 18.24, while demand for CRA pushed the price up 38
cents to ADollars 13.84.
Commonwealth Bank, which reports its interims today, firmed 3 cents to
ADollars 7.13.
NEW ZEALAND partially recovered after results from Telecom and Fletcher
Challenge. The NZSE-40 index was down a net 4.32 at 1,473.03 in turnover of
some NZDollars 18m.
