FT  19 FEB 92 / International Company News: Abitibi-Price maintains dividend
despite reverse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ABITIBI-PRICE, the newsprint and paper producer controlled by Toronto's
Reichmann family, is continuing to pay a dividend despite posting a
substantial loss for the second year in a row.
The Reichmanns own 82 per cent of Abitibi, which cut its annual dividend
from CDollars 1 to 50 cents a share in 1990.
The decision to pay the 12.5 cents-per-share quarterly dividend is widely
interpreted as evidence of the financial strains being felt by the
Reichmanns' heavy exposure to the depressed real estate market through their
holding company, Olympia &amp; York Developments, whose interests include
London's Canary Wharf project.
Abitibi contributed about CDollars 28.4m (USDollars 24.40m) in common-share
dividends to O&amp;Y last year.
Last year's net loss at Abitibi was CDollars 75.9m, or CDollars 1.12 a
share, compared with a CDollars 50.4m, or 76 cents, loss in 1990. The
figures include charges of CDollars 44.4m last year and CDollars 54.1m in
1990 for restructuring to cope with the severe downturn in the Canadian
forest products industry.
Sales fell to CDollars 2.8bn from CDollars 3.1bn, while fourth-quarter sales
tumbled by 23 per cent to CDollars 652m as the newsprint market continued to
be hit by weak demand and intense price competition. The fourth-quarter net
loss deepened to CDollars 48.1m from CDollars 34.7m last time.
Abitibi said the outlook for newsprint remained poor in 1992 and further
cost-cutting measures would be required. The company is expected to announce
the closure of at least one of its eastern Canadian newsprint machines
within the next few months.
An operating loss at Provincial Papers, Abitibi's coated papers division,
wiped out a small operating profit earned by the rest of the company. The
company said a turnround at Provincial was one of its top priorities.
Abitibi said that its balance sheet remained strong, with a debt-to-capital
ratio of 30 per cent. Cash reserves increased by CDollars 100m last year and
cash-flow had been improved by asset sales and belt-tightening.
</TEXT>
