FT  19 FEB 92 / UK Company News: GPG takes 16% stake in Australian
Consolidated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GPG, the London-based investment company managed by Sir Ron Brierley, the
New Zealand entrepreneur, yesterday said it had acquired just over 16 per
cent of the shares of Australian Consolidated Investments.
The announcement fuelled speculation that GPG would bid for ACI, which owns
50 per cent of National Brewing Holdings, formerly the brewing arm of Mr
Alan Bond's Bond Corporation Holdings.
ACI also owns 96 per cent of Weeks Petroleum, an Australian oil company
which has royalty rights over oil produced by Broken Hill Proprietary from
the Bass Strait, off Australia's south coast.
However, ACI is in the process of selling its share in National Brewing to
Lion Nathan, the New Zealand brewer which owns the remaining 50 per cent.
Weeks has also announced plans to float its Bass Strait royalty rights to
raise ADollars 220m (Pounds 94.2m).
Analysts said GPG might seek to prevent ACI disposing of its two principal
assets by bidding for the group, which is capitalised at about ADollars
130m. ACI has also attracted interest from Nycal, a US oil company which has
said it expects to make an announcement shortly. Gulf Resources and Chemical
Corporation, a Nycal subsidiary, said recently that it had tried to acquire
an interest in Weeks' Bass Strait royalties.
ACI, formerly Bell Resources, was once a listed vehicle for Mr Robert Holmes
a Court, the entrepreneur who died in 1990.
