<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Lilley opens way for Redland's bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Lilley, the UK trade and industry secretary, yesterday opened the
way for Redland to pursue its Pounds 629m contested bid for rival UK
building materials group, Steetley.
An opposing plan to merge the British brick, clay roof tile and concrete
product businesses of Tarmac and Steetley was referred for investigation by
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Mr Lilley said an investigation into the Redland offer could still go ahead
if the company was unable to provide satisfactory undertakings to dispose of
brick and clay roof tile plants in markets where it would have a dominant
position. Redland has offered to sell its brick works at Cranleigh in Surrey
and Tilmanstone in Kent as well as the Steetley clay tile plants at Keele
and Knutton in Staffordshire should its bid succeed.
It is thought that the undertakings will be enough to persuade Mr Lilley to
allow the offer to proceed. Redland and Steetley together control 46 per
cent of the national clay roof tile market and 23 per cent of brick
production in south east England.
Some stock market analysts were surprised that Mr Lilley treated the two
merger proposals differently, since both would affect the ownership of a
large part of the UK brick and clay roof tile industry.
Mr Andrew Melrose, construction analyst for Nomura, the Japanese securities
house, said: 'This is a late Christmas present for Redland. Its bid will now
be resolved before the MMC can complete its investigation of the
Tarmac/Steetley joint venture.'
Mr Richard Miles, Steetley's chief executive, said Tarmac and Steetley had
discussed the possibility of giving similar undertakings on disposals but
had been unable to reach agreement with the Office of Fair Trading.
Tarmac and Steetley between them have 39 per cent of the clay tile market,
almost 80 per cent of brick production capacity in north east England and
approaching 50 per cent of brick capacity in south west England.
The large combined turnovers of Steetley and Tarmac mean their joint venture
should have been considered by the European Commission. Sir Leon Brittan the
EC's competition commissioner last week, however, agreed to refer the merger
back to British authorities because of the 'significant competition issues'
raised in the UK.
Mr Miles said last night that Steetley would continue to defend itself
strenuously against Redland's offer of 85 Redland shares for every 100
Steetley shares.
Following yesterday's announcements Redland's share price fell 5p to 473p,
valuing Steetley at Pounds 629m or 402p a share. Tarmac's share price fell
2p to 122p. Tarmac said it would consider its position in the light of the
MMC referral.
Redland said it had always expected it might have to give undertakings on
disposals. Sale of the four plants would have a minimal effect on the
benefits it expected to gain from takeover.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
