<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / The Lex Column: Redland/Steetley
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With yesterday's decision to refer the Tarmac-Steetley joint venture to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission, the options for restructuring Britain's
building materials industry have dramatically narrowed. A Tarmac-Steetley
solution looks dead in the water, perhaps the only outstanding question
being whether Tarmac turns to Ibstock Johnsen for an encore.
On the fairly safe assumption that Redland can now avoid a referral by
submitting undertakings, Steetley is left ever more vulnerable looking down
the barrel of a Pounds 620m bid. Its main defence is anticipated next week,
and will doubtless focus on asset value and Redland's ACT difficulties in an
effort to force up the terms. The market appears to have accepted, though,
that Redland's opening shot was pretty close to the mark. Admittedly there
has been a certain amount of buying interest for the likes of Blue Circle
and RMC since the bid was launched before Christmas - but this has been
highly selective and might well have passed Steetley by. At this stage the
main reason for Redland to sweeten its offer would be to win the
recommendation of the Steetley board.
</TEXT>
